const data={
anderson:{n:"Jonathan Anderson",d:"Fashion · Loewe · JW Anderson · Dior",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Born 1984, Magherafelt, Northern Ireland, during the Troubles. Father was captain of Ireland\'s rugby team. Brother followed into rugby. He chose theater. Moved to New York at 18 to study acting, pivoted to costume design, then fashion. Rejected from fashion schools. Bankrupted himself multiple times building JW Anderson. Now the first person to oversee menswear, womenswear, and couture at Dior since Christian Dior himself. 18 collections a year across three brands.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The private self</div><p>Off social media entirely. Doesn\'t keep his own clothes at home — stores them elsewhere. No design furniture at home. Collects Arts and Crafts ceramics — Baillie Scott, Rennie Mackintosh. Curates exhibitions. Loves orchids. Describes himself as reserved, uncomfortable with the social role of the job. The creative director of two major houses whose private life is the opposite of everything those houses produce.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Works through mind-mapping — radiates outward from a center. Never finishes a collection until the day of the show. When stuck, cleans everything — every cupboard, every window. Physical activity as displacement for creative paralysis. The 2013 ruffled shorts show was attacked for humiliating models. Now regarded as a landmark in genderless fashion. Provocation creates more lasting impact than pleasing.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Doesn\'t sketch on paper. Designs by draping on the body — giving pieces a sculptural quality. "I adore the flat thing. I adore the final image. Fashion is ultimately about trying to sell something through the image, and through desire." The Titian-Rubens method: "The jean will always be the jean. You have to find a new way to represent the jean." So he swagged denim around front pockets until jeans billowed like a Gainsborough skirt. Wrapped denim into an asymmetrical form that drapes like a Sargent gown. Plasticine hoodies — literally modelling clay sculpted into streetwear. Pixel garments fabricated to resemble glitched 8-bit video game images. The Puzzle bag: leather cut into shapes, sliced in half horizontally, glued with reinforcement on all but outer edges, lined with suède — thin enough to stitch without bulk, strong enough for daily use. Artisans tying Flamenco bag knots can only work two hours before rotation — repetitive strain injuries. Learned everything about presentation from Manuela Pavesi at Prada, doing visual merchandising as a student. "She had a precision of putting looks together I had never witnessed. In the beginning, you emulate, and as you gain confidence you become your own thing." Rarely second-guesses his gut instinct. "You realize you\'re no longer eighteen. You have to go off, like Rubens, and make your own language."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Northern Ireland during the Troubles — car bombs, a town getting blown up. But also summers in Ibiza where his parents had a house. The contrasting environments shaped everything. A rugby family that produced a fashion designer. Rejected from every school, bankrupted multiple times, kept going. The pattern: keeps giving up the thing that\'s working to reach the thing that\'s next.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I don\'t take anything for granted because I know that life is like a fuse."</div>'},
kojima:{n:"Hideo Kojima",d:"Gaming",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Father died when he was 13. Came home to an empty house every day after school. That loneliness — chronic, lifelong, never fully resolved — became the subject of every game he has ever made. Death Stranding is a game about a man walking alone across a broken world, building connections between isolated people. The strands that connect them are literal. 30 years of work, one subject. "I want to die while creating something."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">(Re)Sources</div><p>Parents had a nightly film-watching ritual — he wasn\'t allowed to go to bed until the movie was finished. That ritual continued into adulthood. Watches at least one movie every day. Rates them in the iOS Notes app — one thumbs-up means good, two means loved it, an eye emoji means no comment, a heart means he watched it with his son. His mother played Metal Gear Solid 3 with him. Took her six months. She cheated. Four favourite films, always changing: 2001, Taxi Driver, Mad Max 2, Kurosawa\'s High and Low. Goes to art museums almost every week. First god: George Miller. Second god: Scorsese. Joy Division as bedrock. Books, films, music consumed relentlessly. The Creative Gene, his essay collection, reveals how every piece of media he absorbed became material for his work. Watches at least one movie every day. Rates them in iOS Notes with emojis — one thumbs up means good, two means loved it, a heart means watched it with his son. First god: George Miller. Second god: Scorsese. His mother played Metal Gear Solid 3 with him. Took her six months. She cheated.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Total authorship</div><p>Writes, directs, designs, produces — every camera angle hand-placed in a 40-hour experience. Edits the trailers himself. Chooses the structure first, then the song. Reviews an entire trailer in under 10 minutes, gives feedback, moves on. Over seven hours of cutscenes, all made in-house. "I tried delegating at Konami and it didn\'t work. A sequel would be fine. But a completely new game that nobody has ever seen? Even if I wrote something, nobody would understand it." Studied economics because no path into filmmaking existed in Japan. Friends were unsupportive. Family discouraged art. Joined Konami at 23, left after 29 years in a bitter departure. Started over with nothing — no studio, no team, no IP. Built it all back. "If I could make one game a year, I\'d feel so much more at ease. But I can barely manage three games in ten years."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Casting takes four years. Can\'t gather everyone for a three-month shoot like a movie — game development is done as they go, so actors come in regularly for sessions. Photos, scans, data, costumes, makeup — all in very short windows. Léa Seydoux: retaking photos requires three days just to get her teeth scanned. "At this point it\'s like the story of Death Stranding — our bond is really being put to the test." The staff member in charge of Léa\'s face spends several years, almost every day, retouching her facial data. "You can\'t do this unless you love it." By the end of production, that person had bought the actor\'s complete Blu-ray box set — "if you watch it every day, you become a fan." Rewrote the entire Death Stranding 2 story after COVID. "I felt it wasn\'t right, so I rewrote the whole thing." Originally the sequel was about how connecting everyone was a mistake — how to disconnect after they\'d been connected. Casting criteria: "First and foremost, that I like the person." Goes for meals together. Makes sure before deciding. Staff objected to the Like system having no game value — no coins, no levelling up. Kojima insisted. By end of development, the staff who opposed it were happy when they received Likes during testing. Edits every trailer himself — structures it first, chooses the song after. Listens to the game music on the bus, in the car, constantly. Over seven hours of cutscenes, all made in-house.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The cost</div><p>Fell seriously ill during COVID, approaching 60. "I thought I might never be able to make games again." Wrote a will and left it with his secretary. Eye surgery damaged the muscles that adjust focus — used 10 different pairs of glasses before serving as a juror at Venice. "Even if I\'m satisfied today, when I play the same part again tomorrow, it will feel different. That\'s why I have to draw a line and say, this is the end." Scrapped and rewrote Death Stranding 2 during the pandemic because the world had caught up to what he\'d been feeling his entire life. The loneliness that drives the work is also the loneliness of making it. The control is the art. The control is also the isolation. "I won\'t pass the baton. I\'ll just crush it tightly." Directors and musicians contact him saying his games made them who they are. "They\'re not imitating me. They\'ve received the flame and are lighting their own."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I want to die while creating something."</div>'},
brule:{n:"Tyler Brûlé / Monocle",d:"Publishing · Media · Retail",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Record year for profitability — all driven by paper. "When I look at what really puts us in the black as a business, it\'s print." 12 shops and cafes worldwide. Radio station. Books. Newspapers. Retail went from 8% to 20% of revenue. 100 journalists in London. The entire operation is a world built from a magazine.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The frictions</div><p>Unapologetic about people being in the office. "We could sell tickets sometimes because it\'s like a zoo — people are at desks, in the office all day, everything is full and buzzing." Won\'t chase TikTok. "Instagram is great if you\'ve got a hair salon. If you\'re a media brand, I\'m not convinced." Social media is "an event with a glass of wine" — not a platform strategy.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The newsroom</div><p>"A good newsroom is intuitive. I can see someone\'s frown across the room. I can see someone reacting to something on the other side. You\'re able to read the dynamism of that place." The physical space IS the method. Screen-based work is possible but the result is worse.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">On print as luxury</div><p>Siemens — their AI metaverse marketing team — came to discuss a digital partnership. They picked up the Rolex paperback companion and said: "This is the most modern thing I\'ve ever seen." The project became print, almost no digital output. "If you\'re a chief marketing officer, you\'re commoditized if you\'re only on a screen. But if you can pass something around the table, you manufactured something."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>The first shop: a flower shop around the corner went out of business. "It was such a small space. I thought it would be horrible to see some big chain store bulldoze it." Opened as a Christmas popup. Six years later, still there. Now six stores — 15% of the business. The cafe started in Ginza — a Japanese department store asked. Did all the design. It worked. A space opened in London. They seized it. Radio: started with a weekly podcast. Saw commercial life. "Why don\'t we just build two studios and take this around the clock?" Audio is the closest digital medium to the magazine — personal, intimate, incredibly fast. Live broadcast matters: "You sit up straight. Your pitch is different. You get an edginess with live." The ad pages reshuffled by hand yesterday — "to make sure we had a great product." Nothing ad-served by algorithm. "There is still a humanity." Every extension had to make money. No brand exercises. "We don\'t have a diminished or skeptical view about print. We want engaged, quality readers, listeners, viewers. That\'s what\'s important to us."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The independence</div><p>No board member saying chase TikTok. No digital guru. No parent corporation. "If we decide to do a cafe, we do a cafe — because we think it\'s the right thing to do." Organically reinvest everything without going to market. Valued at $115 million after Nikkei invested. Magazine circulation 80,000. $12 in the US, $20 for Forecast — and Forecast is growing at the same rate. "Premium has a bad name in the United States. Everyone wants to chase the mass. We don\'t want big numbers." Subscribers pay $150 a year, no discounts. "They\'re probably more likely to fly on your airline, buy your shoes, or book your hotel than someone in a free channel."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Last year was a record year for us for profitability and growth. It was all about paper."</div>'},
brown:{n:"Cecily Brown",d:"Painting",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes her unique</div><p>Came to New York from London because painting was "not almost embarrassing — it was embarrassing." Used to varnish everything to create distance from the gesture, the paint, the art shame. Signed just her first name on the front — Alex Katz\'s suggestion — because "it really showed it wasn\'t this macho gestural thing." 25 years of toggling between abstraction and figuration.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">(Re)Sources</div><p>A magpie. Copies everything — Hogarth, Snyders, Munch, Fragonard, Manet, Jasper Johns. "I don\'t really know a work of art til I\'ve copied it. It\'s very much a way of committing it to memory, to your painting brain, so you can use it later on." Keeps rubbishy printouts from the computer. Prints things off her phone once a week. Recently started reversing Old Masters when she copies them — mirroring as method.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The mirror</div><p>"I\'m looking back." The woman in the painting who is also the subject of the painting. Double consciousness — aware of yourself but aware of yourself being looked at. "A woman has an advantage when looking at painting, because when you\'re also the subject, it can be much richer and deeper." The cat under the table is the one looking back at you.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How she paints</div><p>No overall scheme. No composition planned. Starts quickly — figures get placed near the beginning. Tries to keep it fluid the whole time. Source material lies on the studio floor, some of it for twenty years. "That looks like the contents of my brain." Rarely holds an image in her hand while painting anymore — lets them enter in a peripheral way. Draws copies of images many times in ink, charcoal, watercolor, then never looks at the drawings again. But they\'re in the room. On large canvases it\'s almost performative — "you\'re basically inside the painting while you\'re working on it." Puts down washes of color at the beginning, then scrapes away. Lets figures emerge naturally. More veils of paint now, less buildup of layers — came from doing large watercolors that fed into the big paintings. "I never think of myself as hiding imagery but things get hidden as you go on. The more you paint, what was there before gets concealed." Looks at paintings through history partly as a technician — "I\'m always thinking, how did they do that?" Then wants to answer. To be in a conversation with other paintings and painters.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Practice</div><p>Can\'t paint from life — "I would kill myself, it\'s too hard." Works from copies, reproductions, found images. 50 canvases at once. Keeps an ongoing list of titles at all times — song lyrics, musicals, pop songs, perfumes, the Bible. "I loathe untitled."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"It\'s almost like if I had to illustrate what I\'m always trying to do with my painting — just the toggling back between one reading of something and another."</div>'},
saarinen:{n:"Karri Saarinen / Linear",d:"Technology",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>At 6 or 7, shopping for bicycles with his family, he looked at the options and couldn\\\'t understand why so many were ugly. Someone chose to make them that way. Why? That question — why do people accept unnecessary ugliness — has driven his entire career. Jira was the ugly bicycle of enterprise software. Linear is the nice bike. Quality as business strategy: profitable by year two, 10,000 paying organisations by year four, almost no marketing spend, almost no sales team. "Because quality is rare, people talk about it. You get free marketing. They get curious. Then they feel it in the product."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Finnish DNA</div><p>All three co-founders are Finnish. The design philosophy comes from Finnish culture — simplicity, function, durability, respect for materials. They barely spent the $52M they raised. Net-negative lifetime burn rate. He talks about Finnish potato farming in the same conversation as venture capital. Moved to Del Mar for quality of life. The company is deliberately calm, deliberately profitable, deliberately unscaled.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Before committing to Linear, the three founders met every Wednesday at a corner table in a bar, brought their computers, talked about what they learned that week. Almost a year of this before quitting their jobs. The product is 80% their intuition, 20% what people asked for. Opinionated defaults against infinite customization. When stuck: add more constraints. The wall reveals the shape of the room. Small teams, no handoffs — iterate together toward the feeling of right. Use intuition over data. "We stopped asking does it convert and started asking does this feel right." Zero bug policy — fix everything in seven days. MVPs used internally, never shipped live until they hit the standard.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>The first Linear website: built in a couple of days. One page. No blog, no about page. Used "issue tracking" as the headline — not "work platform" — because that\'s what their people were searching for. Product screenshot faded and mysterious. "We didn\'t want to spend weeks trying to create a website. The effort should be put into the product itself." Three evolutions of the site since 2019, each matching the company\'s stage. Resisted the urge to overwhelm with features. "The homepage should be for people who don\'t know about you. Enough information that you know if it\'s interesting, but not so much you get overwhelmed." Went from the famous purple website to black and white — "more mature." Still adds effects and animations that signal they care about the experience. "There\'s a danger you go too far trying to look like a large company too early." The product is 80% their intuition, 20% what people asked for.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The friction</div><p>Designed for someone, not everyone. Refuses the Silicon Valley obsession with speed and scale. Previously at Airbnb and Coinbase — saw how hyper-growth dilutes culture. Built the opposite: a venture-scale company that behaves like a craft studio. The founders stay connected to the product because they care about the output, not the org chart.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Why do people do this? If you make a bike, why don\\\'t you make it nice?"</div>'},
browne:{n:"Thom Browne",d:"Fashion",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>One of seven kids in Allentown, Pennsylvania. Economics degree from Notre Dame, competitive swimmer. Tried acting in LA — didn\\\'t work out. Sold his car to get back to New York in 1997. Made five gray suits and wore them himself. The reaction was horror. He kept going. The ridiculed thing became the identity.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The uniform</div><p>Same gray suit every day. Same breakfast. Same morning run. The staff wear the uniform too. When they\\\'re all together it looks like a living piece of art — you don\\\'t see the clothes, you see the whole idea. The consistency IS the freedom. Everything inside the suit can change because the suit never does.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Can\\\'t fashion sketch. Drawings are super abstract, more Bauhausian. Everything starts from proportion and shape, not illustration. Runs 8 miles daily — his mind is free and open when running. The distinction that matters to him: not perfection as a state, but perfect making as a process.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Starts with shapes. A pleated skirt is a triangle. A square is a shorter jacket. A rectangle is outerwear. "I sketch this way because I can\'t actually illustrate, at all." Gets with the team and it turns into a workable sketch. A pattern maker he\'s worked with for years — "a genius" — creates the pattern pieces. Then muslin: the pattern pieces fit on the actual model. "The most important thing is to see that the proportion is working, to see that it actually fits, to see that it\'s something interesting in actuality as opposed to just on paper." Every collection starts from the same question: how do I make the gray suit interesting again? Once proportion and fit are perfected, fabrication. Harris Tweed from a mill where "you won\'t appreciate it, your son won\'t appreciate it, your grandson will appreciate the cashmere." 90% finished in New York, then flown to Paris. The atelier in Paris is year-round — two days before the show, hand finishing. Hours of hand tailoring and hand stitching the conceptual pieces together. Professional dressers who know where to put the tie bar on the tie. Twenty minutes to show what took months to build. "During the show, I can\'t do much so I just enjoy it with everybody else." Sales start the day after. Then onto the next.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The life</div><p>Life partner is Andrew Bolton, curator of the Met Costume Institute. Dachshund named Hector. Almost closed the business in 2009, days away from shutting down. Won the Adidas stripe lawsuit in 2023. Now chairman of the CFDA. The casual world of jeans and t-shirts became the establishment — his world of jackets and trousers became the anti-establishment.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"People think wearing a uniform makes you less interesting, but I think the opposite."</div>'},
kere:{n:"Diébédo Francis Kéré",d:"Architecture",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>First child in his village to go to school. Father was the village chief who couldn\'t read — sent his eldest son away at age 7 to learn to read for him. The village called the father stupid for doing it. The suffocating classroom — 100 children in an unventilated cement block with no light — became the origin of everything. He vowed to make schools better. Then he did. First African to win the Pritzker Prize.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Draws plans in the sand for people who can\'t read. The entire village takes part in construction — children bring one stone each morning, women prepare floors, men press bricks. The community was skeptical about mud bricks — feared rain would destroy them. He had to prove that local material could be better than concrete. The building process IS the architecture.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The return</div><p>Trained as a carpenter in Berlin. Studied architecture at TU Berlin. Could have stayed in Europe. Returned to Gando — one of the poorest places on earth. Gave up the materials palette that Western architecture assumes. Built with clay and laterite instead. Lives in Berlin but returns constantly. The life is the bridge between German technical knowledge and Burkinabè communal knowledge.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Draws plans in the sand for people who can\'t read architectural drawings. The village builds together — not as labourers but as co-authors. Laterite clay from the ground they stand on, pressed into bricks and dried in the sun. Rebar bent by hand. The roof structure of the Gando school: clay pots stacked as ceiling ventilation — air rises through the pots and escapes through a raised corrugated iron roof with a gap. No air conditioning. The building breathes. For the Serpentine Pavilion in London: a great overhanging canopy inspired by the tree in Gando under which the community meets. Wooden shading elements on the underside create shadow patterns that change with the movement of the sun. The walls split into four fragments — four access points — completely detached from the roof so air and visitors circulate freely. For Xylem in Montana: logs grouped in circular bundles within a hexagonal steel structure inspired by the tuguna, the sacred gathering space of Burkinabè communities. Sustainable pinewood sourced locally from a natural pruning process that saves forests from parasitic bugs. Every project starts from the ground — the soil, the climate, the people who will build it and use it. "To build in a particular location means to engage actively with all aspects of the building practices of that place." To explicate is to implicate.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What he protects</div><p>The community\'s agency in their own architecture. If you build with the community, they protect it. If you build for them without them, they watch it decay. The participation isn\'t charity or process theater. It\'s structural. The building is stronger because they built it. The community is stronger because they built it.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>His grandmother\'s storytelling room was his first sense of architecture. Her voice inside the room enclosed them, summoning them closer to form a safe place. The terrible classroom and the beautiful room — two childhood spaces that produced a career. His name was given according to the constellation of the sky.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Everyone deserves quality, everyone deserves luxury, and everyone deserves comfort."</div>'},
torrisi:{n:"Torrisi / Major Food Group",d:"Food",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes them unique</div><p>Rich Torrisi and Mario Carbone met at culinary school in 1998. Both Italian-American, both from New York, both trained under Daniel Boulud. They believed Italian-American food deserved the same reverence as any other cuisine — but the fine-dining world didn\\\'t take it seriously. So they built an empire from the cuisine the establishment dismissed. Carbone, The Grill, Sadelle\\\'s, ZZ\\\'s — all from a genre everyone else saw as uncultured.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Partnership</div><p>Three-person triad: Torrisi handles culinary and menus, Carbone oversees branding, uniforms, plates, cutlery — every sensory dimension. Zalaznick runs new business. Different skill sets, common goal. When Zalaznick first sat down with Carbone, they talked for six hours and discovered they\\\'d been dreaming of the same restaurant. Carbone on concepting: "It always starts with a story. You tell it to designers, architects, craftsmen making your plates. Then it trickles down to staff and training." The captain system: trained like chefs, know everything. "Our captains will never come and ask me anything. They\'re me in the dining room."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">(Re)Sources</div><p>Built into the frame of the past. The former Rocco space became Carbone — the neon sign glows over the original Rocco sign, honoring the neighborhood\\\'s history. Italian-American food from their own childhoods — Queens, Westchester, Mulberry Street — treated with fine-dining rigor. The nostalgia isn\\\'t decorative. It\\\'s the architecture.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The private self</div><p>Torrisi: lives near Washington Square Park, goes there daily with his dog. Cycles Central Park, runs under bridges. Eats cardamom coffee from Punjabi Deli, salt baked squid from Chinatown noodle shops, hot dogs with the works. The man behind the $60 veal parm eats street food and goes for late-night squid in Chinatown.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Cooking is at its best a spontaneous mood. "How excited can I get about this one thing right now?" Got the Puck Building space on a shoestring during COVID — bandaged everything, forced it to work. 200 people every night, Monday or Saturday, January or June — same number. "How can we do these 200 people better than we did yesterday?" Now going back slowly, rebuilding — a new open kitchen designed for how they cook, a new lounge, the barroom brought up to the level of the back room. No bad seat. "Every little thing we would have done if our budget was 3x, 4x." The wooden spoon: medium-small, high quality wood. "It\'s an extension of your hands — you can feel the food in your hand." The chalkboard keeps it fresh — specials that change with the mood. "The biggest most brilliant beautiful flavors while concurrently being light. That\'s what great cooking is."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The life</div><p>"I\'m a really good synthesizer and editor. I can bring things together that might not seem to go together." Runs hot — "smash into a wall, calm down, get energy back, run hot, smash into a wall." Takes himself to Montauk. Slow cooking for family and friends. "I enjoy peeling an onion slow. I put the music on and do everything slow and enjoy every bit of it." That brings him back to the craft. Greatest restaurant experience: Etxebarri. Six-hour lunches on the patio overlooking the mountain. "The chef never gets in the way of the ingredients. Like a sushi chef — an ambassador of great ingredients." Eats sushi 30 to 40 percent of the time he goes out. "Our highest goal: make moments you\'ll never forget. A living room, not an operating room."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Italian food gets a tremendous amount of attention in New York, but Italian-American food doesn\\\'t get so much play at all."</div>'},
herndon:{n:"Holly Herndon & Mat Dryhurst",d:"Music · AI · Technology",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes them unique</div><p>The practitioners who complicate the thesis. They don\'t resist AI — they author their relationship with it. Holly trained an AI on her own voice (Spawn). Holly+ lets anyone sing in her voice. Spawning builds consent tools for artists in AI datasets. Too pro-AI for the art world, too pro-artist for the tech world. The intellectual loneliness of refusing to join either camp.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Holly grew up singing in a church choir in East Tennessee. The church was her social life — music as part of communion, ritual, coming together. That communal singing, lost when she left, is what she\'s been rebuilding with technology ever since. East Tennessee church choir to Berlin techno to Stanford PhD to AI art. Each displacement becomes material.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Partnership</div><p>Met through a podcast — Holly sent an angry email about a late release. Married a year later. 17 years together. Had a baby during COVID. Holly emerged from postpartum into the AI explosion. Decentralized studio in Berlin: GPUs at home, meeting space nearby, sound studio elsewhere, 3D printing in another district. The partnership is romantic, creative, and structural — built into the systems they make.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Machine learning models as art medium. Every step in the model creation process is a moment for creative intervention. Training ceremonies where participants sing to the AI. 15 UK choirs recorded for The Call at the Serpentine. The audience contributes the data. The collaboration is open-source and governed.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How they make it</div><p>Intervene in every step of the AI model creation process — deliberately producing training data, captioning it, setting the protocol for how to interact with it. Each step is a moment for creative decision. For Holly+: recorded 15 UK choirs singing specific material. Holly sings to Holly+ and it sings back in real time — her voice filtered through hundreds of other voices that trained the model. "AI is just us, in aggregate — it is beautiful and requires rethinking how we arrange life." For The Call at the Serpentine: detailed relief sculptures, suspended structures, immersive spatial audio. Worked with architecture studio sub on how physical space might encourage "a spirit of contemplative contribution to the human archive." Training ceremonies where participants sing to the AI — positioning it as part of a lineage going back to group singing rituals that predate language. Always at least five projects going at once. Between art, tech work, and parenting, "we basically share a brain at this point." Met when Holly emailed Mat\'s label asking why their podcast was late. Married nearly 20 years. Their studio is essentially countless communication channels. Now training Public Diffusion with Spawning — a foundational text-to-image model trained only on data that nobody owns.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Why they matter here</div><p>The false binary is: you\'re either pro-AI or pro-artist. They reject that completely. The question isn\'t resistance or submission. It\'s governance — who decides, who consents, who benefits. Spawning is the infrastructure that lets artists say yes or no. The resistance isn\'t against the technology. It\'s against the absence of choice.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"AI is us, in aggregate, with emergent properties."</div>'},
philo:{n:"Phoebe Philo",d:"Fashion",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes her unique</div><p>First woman to take maternity leave at a major fashion house. Left Céline in 2018. Spent years deliberating. Returned on her own terms — no shows, no seasons, no storytelling. Majority owner. Started with maybe two staff members. The silence was never absence. It was the position. At Chloé, she and McCartney were "the naughty kids from London" — McCartney in oversized jackets, Philo in a set of gold teeth. Worked with the late rock tailor Edward Sexton on their earliest suiting. When McCartney left, Philo single-handedly redirected the house — less rock, more suave casual elegance. The Paddington bag increased Chloé\'s global sales by 60%. At Céline, her Crombie coat was interfaced in canvas — a menswear construction technique giving it armour-like rigidity rarely found in women\'s clothing. Joan Didion at 80 in the campaign. As she matured, her work matured. "The work of a woman working for women, who simply gets it." Reworking her own clothes as a teenager. Pumps that looked like bare feet with red-painted toenails. Belts shaped like magnified chain links. The conceptual joke inside the practical garment. "Contemporary minimalism" was her own phrase — but anyone who sees Philo as purely minimalist misses the boldness and playfulness that emerged over the years.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The refusal</div><p>Won\'t do storytelling. Won\'t do seasons. Won\'t do social media. Won\'t do interviews — first in 10 years. Won\'t accept the pace of fashion. "To a certain extent you either like it or you don\'t. Someone telling me a story isn\'t going to make me like it more. It is a coat. It\'s a pair of trousers."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What she protects</div><p>Independence — even at the cost of comfort. Gave up first class, drivers, orchids in the office. "Fundamentally that is not the stuff that makes me happy." What makes her happy: baking, galleries, riding, clubbing, family, friends. The work and the life are deliberately kept in balance, not merged.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How she makes it</div><p>Works on the stand — manipulating fabric to create detail and shape. Not sketching at a desk but draping, cutting, adjusting on the dress form. "I like slightly heavier fabrics that you can cut into and create a silhouette, mixed with lighter fabrics." One wall of the studio pinned with colour photocopies from books and magazines. Her office bare except for snapshots of her daughter. Works with a team of five key designers — let them take the bow at her first show back from maternity leave. "I did not feel like bullshitting. It was not my work and I was not going to walk out at the end." Designs come back from the Paris atelier and half the time she thinks "Hell, what is that!" Every day adjusting and rethinking. Work in progress right up until the show. "Even then you are never quite sure how things are going to happen. But that is the nature of the beast." Splits between London and Paris — eight days a month in Paris, the rest in London. "I try not to intellectualise what I do. In fact, I\'ve always been rather shit at that." The clothes are emotional. "Rather than deny that, I allow myself to work on that. I think that is what the customers respond to."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Views her work as one continuous collection. Rejects the word "season," prefers "edit." "It takes time and effort to make most things that have meaning. One has to stand for something." The pace is hers, not the industry\'s.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I don\'t know why there has to be such a beginning and end in our industry. I don\'t know why it just can\'t be continuous."</div>'},
therow:{n:"The Row",d:"Fashion · Mary-Kate + Ashley Olsen",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes them unique</div><p>Cast at nine months old. Personhood consumed by celebrity before they had selves. At one point their home video sales were second only to Disney. Built The Row as the exact inversion — anonymous, silent, authorless. Durable where the childhood work was disposable. Invisible where the childhood was overexposed. Founded it at 20 — named after London\'s Savile Row. No one knew they were behind it at first. The original idea: designing the perfect shirt. Over the years they\'ve maintained this process — identify an everyday garment and obsessively refine it. A sort of upscale, trend-conscious secular nun\'s uniform.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The refusal</div><p>Neither on Instagram. No press. No announcements of pregnancies or marriages. "Most of the time we\'re saying no to things so we can be more in control. That\'s what we protect." Still majority owners after 17 years. Growth at 20-30% annually but only as fast as they can handle. Banned cell phones at the Paris resort show — staff learned days before, had to execute a full photo shoot on top of the runway, pulled an all-nighter. The result was nice. When Prada appeared to copy the Margaux bag, staff were shocked and upset. Secrecy is their most valuable PR tool. Cate Blanchett\'s character in Tár wears a Row coat — it practically blew the film\'s wardrobe budget.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The body knows</div><p>Mary-Kate, asked where she\'s happiest: "On the floor with some pins and some scissors." Ashley: "Adjusting and shaping a garment." Model Małgosia Bela on the atmosphere: "People talk in lowered voices, everyone is focused. It reminds me of working for Comme des Garçons 25 years ago."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What they notice</div><p>The difference that isn\'t visible. Styling variations where even the model wearing the outfit doesn\'t see much difference. And yet, there is a difference. They\'re hypersensitive to what their customers already own. They don\'t design into trends — they design into what\'s missing from a wardrobe.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Anonymity is a luxury as well."</div>'},
lemaire:{n:"Christophe Lemaire",d:"Fashion",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Started at 19. Never learned pattern cutting — calls it his biggest regret. The entire label compensates: "chic and utilitarian" since 1991 is a man who perfects what his eye can do because his hands can\'t. Still sketches by hand — "I\'m an old guy, I still sketch, which is rare these days." Creative director at Lacoste, then Hermès womenswear, then back to independence with co-artistic director Sarah-Linh Tran. 8 designers plus the two of them, all very hands-on.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Scénario first — the pitch for the collection. Then fabric, then silhouette, then product piece by piece. Albums before songs. "Sarah-Linh and I start talking, we talk with the team, we start doing silhouettes, sharing images, working from vintage pieces or pieces from the Lemaire archives. There\'s no one recipe." Everything modular — good clothes mix with other things. Then: "What do you need every day? The storage, the pocket system, the movement, the weather, the breathability." Combine utilitarian design with something interesting in proportion or styling. Take something archetypal and find ways to twist it. Then add strangeness and irrationality — "if they don\'t have any irrationality, they might be boring." Works in nuances: faded colours, smoky colours. "Sometimes people think it\'s just 50 shades of mushroom." Very consistent base of pieces, with new explorations in fabrication, style, colours. "We\'re not Margaret Howell. I have huge respect for her consistency, but there\'s more than that in what we\'re interested in."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">(Re)Sources</div><p>"All the unsung heroes of workwear and military wear. The unknown designers and pattern cutters who designed military wear, who worked at Levi\'s. That\'s real design." Greatest designer of all time: "The Japanese designers from the 80s. Yohji, especially for menswear. Some aspects of Miyake. Rei Kawakubo." Current admiration: Kaptain Sunshine, Auralee, Comoli — "a more humble approach than designers. Proposing a good menswear wardrobe, reworking archetypes in a cool way." Grew up with punk, post-punk and dub.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What he protects</div><p>No logos. A small leather "LEMAIRE" tab on the back waistband of their denim caused internal revolt: "They told me it was a crime. It was like pornography for them." No plans for big expansion. "We don\'t have dreams of big expansion. We could stay where we are right now. We\'d never put a logo just to sell more. We want the interest of the product to be enough." "We don\'t like people that wear clothes to show off social status. We don\'t like style as a social disguise. We\'re interested in style as something deeper, something to do with feeling yourself."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Partnership</div><p>Sarah-Linh Tran as co-artistic director since 2014. Ten people total on the design team. When Lemaire returned to independence, they brought no synthetics — all natural fabric. Now they use nylons and polymers when the fabric demands it — "a certain lightness, a certain dryness, which is very hard to find with all-natural fabric."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The private life</div><p>Not a fetishist, doesn\'t collect objects. Treasures a $2,500-rare piano LP by Su Tissue — a post-punk musician from Suburban Lawns who made one minimalist record and vanished. "She made this beautiful piece of music, and then she disappeared."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Who designed the first trench coat?"</div>'},
robertson:{n:"Chad Robertson / Tartine",d:"Food",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Rootlessness. No fixed home, constant moving as a child, exchange students as best friends. Wherever he lands, he builds community through bread. SF, LA, Seoul — the bakery is the social infrastructure. The rootless person whose work is about making roots for others.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Four ingredients, 38-page recipe. Baking bread is not about controlling the process — it\'s about guiding the fermentation. The attention is inversely proportional to the ingredient count. The simplest thing demands the deepest knowledge.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Point Reyes Station. A bucket, a table, and a wood-fired oven. No mixer. Everything mixed by hand. Started the day chopping wood and feeding the sourdough — just flour and water, let it ferment. Built the fire in the morning. It burned for eight hours while he mixed doughs. Somewhere in the middle, baked the bread that was made the day before. Then shaped all the bread and let it rise overnight for the next day. Always a two-day process that overlapped. To stretch the rising time and develop more flavour, he opened the windows at night and let the whole bakery cool down. Worked for part of the year. In summer it didn\'t — sleep went from eight hours to five. Completely unsustainable. Seven days a week. Some days stayed in pyjamas and worked all day. "I was like the white rhino. You could look through the window and see me in there working. Making really great bread, but definitely a one-trick white rhino." Tasted real bread for the first time at 20 in Massachusetts — sourdough, the most primordial way bread was made. Instantly decided. That deep dive in a solitary trance state gives you the basic knowledge so you can start playing with the rules. Now: wood-fired oven next to the most high-tech thermal oil oven built in Germany. "Tradition should inform the innovation, not constrain it. Innovation should complement the tradition, not replace it."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Long patience</div><p>6 years developing grain with Washington State bread lab before using it at Tartine. The question was: when can I use these? And it took six years. The process of learning never ends — that\'s the point, not the obstacle.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The friction</div><p>His own team pushes back: "Chad, that\'s not Tartine." He fights stasis disguised as tradition. Wants to kill the morning bun but can\'t — working on making it excite him again. The enemy isn\'t failure. It\'s the comfort of the thing that already works.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Relationships</div><p>Richard Bourdon, his teacher. Elisabeth Prueitt, co-founder and partner. Jennifer Latham, Director of Bread. The practice is relational at every level — teacher, partner, protégé. And the neighbourhood: everyone stops to chat with Chad. You meet half the neighbourhood walking with him. The bakery creates a community, not just bread.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"We never mastered this. We never stopped learning. We can always do better."</div>'},
nakamura:{n:"Hiroki Nakamura / Visvim",d:"Fashion · Craft",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Teenager drawn to American outdoor gear. Asked why it was cool. Realized it was the purpose, not the appearance — boots made for mountain climbing, not for city streets. Spent 22 years closing the gap between surface and essence. "It\'s no good just chasing after what\'s visually apparent on the outside. You have to get to the heart of the matter."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What he protects</div><p>His own sensory apparatus. No TV, no newspapers, no movies — "nothing commercial." At antique markets, ignores the merchant and reads the maker\'s emotional state from the object. "If you put too much soy sauce on something, you can\'t taste it, and if you stay in an inorganic space for a long time, your senses become numb." For Hiroki, "afford" means accomplishing everything without compromising vision. First Tokyo store in a basement across from an elementary school. "That was the best I could do, but it was still cool."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Sees his role as connector between artisans and market. "Artisans are treasures to me." Many different makers involved in manufacturing — people who take pride in their skills and hone their craft every day. Values the Japanese and German Meister cultures. "In other countries, people are often just workers, not artisans. The crucial difference is the passion."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Every thread, fabric, dye, and trim made completely bespoke, every product, every season, by a global constellation of artisanal workshops. Spends weeks on the exact twist of a yarn. Months making a coat a precise shade of red. Years chasing a specific texture for a pair of jeans. Found a tribal workshop on the Chinese-Vietnam border — collected vintage fabric from the 19th century and asked them to remake it. They did. Hand-drawn designs scanned so they can be emailed — "I want to use computer technology to make a thing beautiful, not to just try to make it more easily." Loses one or two supplier workshops every season — "especially small workshops in Japan." GORE-TEX ended a 16-year partnership because they don\'t do small projects anymore. His production team travels from Japan to Italy to France to LA. Wakes at 5am, makes breakfast, takes his daughter to school. Designs in LA now — "other cities can be very heavy. Here it feels lighter and more neutral." On the curb outside the store, mid-conversation, he looks down at his own trousers and drifts off — "I don\'t like this part, so I\'m taking some space out of here and adding here instead..." His wife: "He\'s always talking about the product."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The life</div><p>Met Kelsi when she was a vintage dealer in New York stocking his archive. "She was already a part of my creative process." Asked her to design the women\'s line. Stopped drinking and eating red meat in LA. Their daughter Riko wears Christo sandals to school. His 1957 Porsche refused to start — thirty minutes of tinkering, a drinking straw of gas dripped into the carburetor. Finally: jumper cables. "Should we go get coffee?" A Kyoto mechanic worked 3.5 hours and refused payment: "This repair is a gift from Kyoto."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"No one can teach you, so you need to consciously try to feel for yourself."</div>'},
portorocha:{n:"Porto Rocha",d:"Design · Leo Porto + Felipe Rocha",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes them unique</div><p>Felipe: from a very poor neighbourhood in São Paulo. "If there wasn\'t any homophobia in Brazil, I would have pursued a career as a dancer. Design was a way to express my creativity, but it was not as gay." Leo: convinced everything from abroad was better, until his first internships proved he was just as good. Both spent years trying to copy European design before realizing their background was the differentiator.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Partnership</div><p>Started freelancing together to spend time together as a couple. "People say don\'t mix dating and working, but it ended up working for us." Now 30 people. The five-year party doubled as networking, but business was never the first goal.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What they protect</div><p>Collaboration over hierarchy. "We don\'t support the old school work structure of a single design \'mastermind\' dictating direction." Also protect against free pitches — launched nofreepitches.com, got nearly 7,000 signatures. "We were being exploited by a system where they use \'interesting\' projects as bait for agencies to compete against each other."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How they make it</div><p>Robin Hood rebrand: simplified the iconic feather to reveal the rising arrow hidden inside. Stripped the colour palette to black, white, neutrals — then created space for one electric yellow-green they call Robin Hood neon. Typography: Phonic for utility, Martina Plantijn for warmth. Replaced sci-fi illustrations that couldn\'t scale with geometric, chart-inspired graphics — 70 illustrations, all animated. Then photography as metaphor: a closeup of a double-yolked egg for returns, a bicycle cassette for speed, a praying mantis for your financial journey. Multiple Figma files deep. "We need to try a lot of things and eventually you arrive on something that makes sense. That\'s how we design." "No matter how good the design solution is, it only works when both parts are equally invested — the agency and the client." Less is more as Mies meant it — not lazy, but intentional. "That\'s pretty much what we did in each one of the brand elements."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The proof</div><p>Rebranding MASP and Kunsthalle Basel — Brazilians designing for Swiss institutions. The full-circle moment. Felipe: "I became much happier with myself and the result of my work when I understood that what is special about it is my background and where I come from."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"My work got so much better when I understood that what is special about it is my background and where I come from."</div>'},
sato:{n:"Oki Sato / Nendo",d:"Design · Architecture",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Born in Canada, arrived in Japan at 11. The outsider who sees what natives take for granted. "Mechanical pencils that extend when you shake them, erasers that collect shavings, candy lids that can be resealed. The things Japanese people take for granted are cool." Designed ballpoint pens and gum packaging with the same attention as the Japan Pavilion for the Osaka-Kansai Expo. Nendo means playdough in Japanese — "trying to blend together not only architecture but interiors and small objects." First showed in Milan at Salone Satellite in 2003 when there were two or three Japanese designers. Now: "A lot of young Japanese designers see it as if Nendo can do it, we can do it."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">(Re)Sources</div><p>Shikinen Sengu: Ise Grand Shrine rebuilt every 20 years. No blueprints — only techniques passed down. "Not passing down things, but techniques." When nendo tried to recreate it, they couldn\'t make a model. Had Doraemon explain it in a comic strip.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What he protects</div><p>Ambiguity. Wanted "softer, more ambiguous communication, rather than a condescending \'this is the way it is!\'" Didn\'t want to present answers — wanted hints. "I wanted everyone to take the \'answer\' home and find it for themselves."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Begins by conceiving a story that generates emotional value. Then considers the most suitable colours, materials, forms, and techniques to suit it. "It\'s like fitting puzzle pieces together — a very logical process." Three key elements connected to emotion: colour, material, and form. Balances and prioritises these three for every project. Memory is the key, emotion is the door. "Using the right key allows you to open the door." Prefers broadly shared memories over specific ones — experiences many people have in common. The Peg Chair came from watching cute cars scoot around Milan. The Cabbage Chair: Issey Miyake asked for a chair from the pleated paper normally thrown away in making pleated fabric. No assembly — shipped as a roll, the user peels it open. The Mimicry Chairs: ten chairs placed throughout the V&amp;A, each modified to mimic the space and objects around it. Conducting daily experiments for years — translating expressions of natural materials like wood and stone onto industrial materials like metal and resin. "No final output yet." The observation is the practice. "The most successful designs begin as simple ideas that evoke an honest and empathetic response."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Radical non-hierarchy. Design team, architecture team, and interior team all in the same meetings. "It was like a soccer game with elementary school kids, where everyone is swarming around one ball." Deliberately rejected the stable Japanese construction process — "If the construction process is the same, the results will inevitably be similar."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"It\'s like the joy of unexpectedly finding something you\'ve lost, even though buying something new is fun."</div>'},
collins:{n:"Brian Collins & Leland Maschmeyer / COLLINS",d:"Design",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes them unique</div><p>Brian wanted to animate for Disney as a child. Yellow Ball Workshop, stop-motion with cardboard cutouts. Became a graphic designer instead — brought animation into design. Leland straddles design and business, reads Greek mythology and French deconstructionist philosophy in the same week as pricing strategy and private equity models. Together they run COLLINS — named design firm of the year by Ad Age three times. "Design is the creation of intentional change. I will die on this hill." Not a design studio anymore. A transformation consultancy that works with CEOs, boards, and private equity firms.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Patterns</div><p>Leland\'s thesis: all innovation begins with pattern. Batman succeeded where The Red Bee failed because Batman drew on the redemption pattern — Eden, the fall, the cave, the animal skin, the return. Whether Bob Kane knew it or not. Einstein played Mozart obsessively because he believed Mozart had found a hidden pattern in the universe — and credits that discovery with influencing the theory of relativity. Hamilton married hip-hop patterns with American mythology. Nike is the story of Hercules. Chobani was built on the mythology of paradise. "We don\'t create new patterns. We reinterpret them. Their reinterpretations might obscure the source, but it always goes back to natural patterns."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The quartz crisis</div><p>In 1969, the Seiko Astron destroyed Swiss watchmaking. Quartz was more accurate and 80% cheaper. 1,600 watchmakers became 600. The survivors leaned into complications — mechanical features you can\'t reduce to a circuit board. The industry emerged stronger than before. "AI is our quartz revolution. The value of design won\'t be found in its form. It\'ll be found in how the system performs." At COLLINS they call the response augments — performance features built into identity systems. Brian: "AI has eliminated the craft mode. This is how it goes." Leland: "We had a window to build economic value around a powerful discipline. We fumbled it. We preached the gospel of design instead of capturing its value."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Partnership</div><p>Brian protects the team, not the hero. Names every team member on every project. "Nothing great is made alone." Both parents passed within two months — "my team accelerated while I was gone." Hosts a quiet garden gathering during Cannes Lions for young people who can\'t afford tickets. Leland left COLLINS for five years to become chief brand officer at Chobani — transformed a yogurt company into a wellness platform. Came back as CEO. Low power gap culture — the most junior designer can say "I don\'t think this works" and be heard. Leland on knowing when design is working: "If your passion isn\'t connecting to what\'s happening, your body is saying this doesn\'t make sense." And: "If you can\'t distill it down to something super simple, you don\'t fully understand it yet."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"When you\'re explaining, you\'re losing."</div>'},
reed:{n:"Jesse Reed / Order",d:"Design · Publishing",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Youngstown, Ohio. $3,000 and a Craigslist air mattress. Three years of silence at Pentagram, absorbing Bierut. When he told Bierut he was leaving: "I knew it. I just thought maybe you\'d wait another year." Then a hug. Founded Order with Hamish Smyth over breakfast in Atlanta — by the end of a long walk they had a name, a domain, and email accounts. Five hours from idea to plan. The disorder of arriving with nothing becomes the career of making everything legible.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">(Re)Sources</div><p>Found the NYCTA manual in Pentagram\'s basement while looking for a tarp to cover a foosball table. At Herman Miller\'s archive in Zeeland, Michigan: handwritten letters from Charles and Ray Eames, John Massey\'s design work, Alexander Girard\'s textiles, Stephen Frykholm\'s posters. Gage &amp; Tolner\'s original 1879 signage behind Arby\'s fake walls. The Herman Miller archive in Zeeland, Michigan — handwritten letters from Charles and Ray Eames. "We go back into the archives and pull out some old logo and then make it that."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>One designer per project, start to finish. Learned from Bierut: "Each designer is responsible for the research, the presentations, and the deliverables. There\'s no competition. You own this." The bookstore in front of the Greenpoint studio has landed clients — Adidas walked in for a book and walked out commissioning a brand identity.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Herman Miller came with an identity unchanged for 25 years. Reed\'s instinct wasn\'t to redesign. "Some designers want a visible hand in the new chapter. In this case, we approached the process very delicately, making sure not to pull out any foundational bricks." Went to Zeeland, Michigan, deep into the archives. Found handwritten letters from Charles and Ray Eames. Found that before 1980, the brand had been bold, vibrant, expressive — then gradually muted into 90s corporate. "Almost immediately, Garrett and I looked at each other and didn\'t need words to signal what we were going to do." Irving Harper\'s M symbol: freed it from the circle it had been trapped in for decades. Started treating it like the 50s and 60s — scaled up, pushed around, repeated. Arrived at the first presentation with a single typeface proposal: Söhne by Klim. The client asked for alternatives. Explored them. The original choice proved its worth. "The key component to a successful outcome is not great typography — it\'s trust." One designer per project, start to finish. Learned from Bierut at Pentagram: "Each designer is responsible for the research, the presentations, and the deliverables. There\'s no competition. You own this." The name came from Vignelli: "If you can design one thing, you can design anything." They tried Anything, then Everything — then realized they can\'t design a chair or a car. "How do we approach design? We organise and put everything in order."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The private life</div><p>Pop punk kid. Plays drums in Shark Swimmer. Eats Taco Bell before practice. Apartment is immaculate — "people come and they\'re like, did you do this for me?" Bobby Flay, when asked for a recipe: "Do I ask you how to do graphic design?"</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"My MO is that I just don\'t want to get fired or fuck something up."</div>'},
moniker:{n:"Moniker / Luna Maurer + Roel Wouters",d:"Design · Interactive",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes them unique</div><p>Designed for the optimism of the early web — then watched platforms hollow it out. Two manifestos: Conditional Design (process over outcome) and Designing Friction (bringing physical engagement back to digital culture). "We propose that people engage with their whole body, all senses, getting together — rather than everybody isolated, smooth behind their screens."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The friction</div><p>"A ball rolling over a surface — they dance beautifully together, but they need each other." Roel: "It\'s not a metaphor. It might be the same force, literally. You need collision in order to engage." They fear comfort most: "All these concepts that come along with AI is all about ease. You don\'t have to sweat anymore. This mindset is not how we get connected."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The refusal</div><p>Won\'t use AI as co-author. Experimented extensively. "When you use AI as a co-creator, it\'s often so boring. We got bored." No AI in the final film. "We can say more about AI by not using it." Dissolved the studio after 15 years rather than continue on wrong terms. "Our work was never a recipe you can give to others." Won\'t use AI as co-author.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Participatory filmmaking. Deep Soup had 100 contributors filming primary verbs — falling, floating, sinking, rolling, breaking, collapsing. Luna dragged her family into a rainstorm to film something floating. "We had the best time of our life." The phone is the tool, but the experience is physical. Neither Luna nor Roel codes — they worked with programmers who could execute their concepts. The craft was in the system design, not the code.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How they make it</div><p>Conditional Design was written over almost a year, every Tuesday in Luna\'s kitchen — four people, writing it down. "We came from graphic design — static media, books, posters. We wanted to emphasize design as something that evolves, grows, changes over time. The result is not a fixed formation but a continuous process." "The craftsmanship is in the design of the rules and constellations, rather than in the brush stroke." Studying behaviour like an ant farm — "we place people, make this little maze or exercise, and study what their behavior is. For years that was super satisfying." Performances in concert buildings where the audience becomes participant. Floor sticker installations in museums. Participatory video clips. Films. "We don\'t fit any box." For Deep Soup: gave 100 contributors phones and primary verbs — falling, floating, sinking, rolling, breaking. Luna dragged her family into a rainstorm. "We had the best time of our life."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What they notice</div><p>Boredom is being eliminated. "At the moment you feel uncomfortable you pick up your phone and scroll and then it\'s gone. The things that normally happen when you\'re bored — doubt, sadness — from that a lot of initiative starts." Technology was supposed to connect everyone. "The web changed from a platform where you could publish or make something to infrastructure for big tech." They don\'t give answers. They design environments where questions become visible.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"One can only dance if the other one helps."</div>'},
anderson_c:{n:"Christopher Anderson",d:"Photography",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>A "professional noticer" — his own term. Not there to decorate a magazine. There to observe and be the eyes for the public. Started in war zones: Haiti, Afghanistan, Iraq, Gaza. Then his son Atlas was born, and he realized the family work wasn\'t a side project. It was the practice. "Everything I had been doing up until this point I had been doing to prepare me to make these pictures now."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Two. An NBA injury ended a basketball career. The spatial intelligence from the court — reading movement, anticipating bodies in space — became the camera eye. Then, in 2000, he boarded a 23-foot wooden boat with 44 Haitians sailing for America. The boat began to sink. A Haitian named David said, "Chris, you\'d better start making pictures. We only have an hour to live." They were rescued. Later, he asked himself: why make pictures no one will ever see? "The act of photographing had more to do with explaining the world to myself than explaining something to someone else." The single most transformative moment of his photographic life.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What he protects</div><p>The unretouched truth. His White House portraits showed every pore, every injection mark, every paint chip on the wall. "I made a choice in photographing her choices in a way that is revealing about her choices." In the age of AI filters, he protects the blemish. Some family images he keeps private — the protection runs both ways.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he shoots</div><p>On the boat in Haiti, saying goodbye to each other, assuming they had an hour to live — he made photographs. Reflexively. "Why would I make photographs that I assumed no one would ever see? The only answer: I was trying to explain the world to myself." That crystallised everything. Not telling a story, not reporting facts, not describing something. "Trying to convey what it felt like to be there." Started at small local newspapers, covering small events. "I remember getting a small assignment and trying to do a good job on it. Then a slightly larger assignment. That was the closest thing I had to a strategy." Rose to one of the world\'s top war photographers — Iraq, Afghanistan, Lebanon, Palestine. Then Atlas was born in a loft in Williamsburg above a sculptor\'s studio, in a building called the Kibbutz, one step up from a squat. Tim Hetherington lived in the same building. When Hetherington was killed by shrapnel in Libya, Anderson stopped photographing conflict. Turned his lens to his son. "The smallest gesture from my son, in the most quiet, still moments, had the capacity to contain more power than anything I had witnessed before." Moved from New York to Paris during the pandemic. Unpacked his studio. Looked through the Haiti work and realized he\'d missed all the best images. "I was looking for a picture that would impress somebody. Now I don\'t care about that. I care about the images that express how I felt at the time."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Shoots film. Stands so close that Susie Wiles told him to back up. Seated Stephen Miller beneath an oil painting of Native Americans returning home on horseback — "I hoped people might see it. Go look, go look for it." The composition is the commentary. The journalism is in the frame, not the caption.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"These are the most important pictures that I will make in my lifetime."</div>'},
arnold:{n:"Daniel Arnold",d:"Photography",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>A student of discomfort. Walks 8 hours a day, every day, because fear is the engine. "Any time I\'m afraid, even if I do fail, it\'s the most rewarding work. Those are the photos I\'m most attached to and most proud of. The ones I had to be afraid to get." Shoots down by his waist and looks away. Hasn\'t overcome the fear of photographing strangers. Doesn\'t intend to. "Nothing gets figured out. Nothing gets easier. You\'re still scared. You still don\'t know what the fuck\'s going on, but you just get used to being scared."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Milwaukee to New York at 23 — "this soaking wet, brand new kid who didn\'t have the nerve to go inside of a bar." The camera as belonging device: it gave him an excuse to enter a room where he had no apparent purpose. Writer at MTV and Nickelodeon before photographer. First trip abroad at 33 — overdrew his bank account paying for the cab to JFK, landed in Paris with negative money, slept on the floor of an art forger\'s studio, walked 20 miles a day starving. Dined with Vogue editors at night. "They\'d come from all day glamour. And I\'d come from all day mess."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What drives him</div><p>The terror of going numb. Walking began as a depression release valve. Over time it became addiction, then method — a way of staying permanently available to the world. "I put an irrational, crazy amount of time and energy into just being available, being outside, being ready, paying attention." He protects naivety, protects fear, protects the discomfort — because comfort is where the seeing stops.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he shoots</div><p>Most of the photographs are taken from the hip. Literally. Doesn\'t look through the viewfinder. "Unless I use the viewfinder, you don\'t know I\'m taking a picture." Swivels 45 degrees, takes the shot, lowers the camera, keeps walking — the act brings no attention. "The surprise of a picture is so much more gratifying when you relinquish control, when you feel more like a conduit than a craftsman." The real value of going out every day — mediocre pictures, occasionally a good one — is building a virtual library in your head of minor failures. "This failure cumulatively informs the idea of what you\'re looking for. The next time the world is on the verge of doing a similar thing, you are more likely to tune into it in time to catch it." Started with an iPhone as a spy camera — "I could stick the iPhone right up your nose and you would never know." Instagram gave the pictures a use. Then switched to film, to a rangefinder, to keep learning instead of becoming a prisoner of the social media splash. Editing: the cheap satisfaction of "it\'s in focus and it\'s in the box" wears off over time. On assignment he functions "like a chicken with its head cut off. The whole operation is a fucking scam. Nobody knows what they want. I know how to take a picture without thinking about it."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The work</div><p>Made $15K in a single day selling 4x6 prints at $150 on Instagram. In the past three years: lost a father, a grandfather, an uncle, a younger brother, and a cat. "I\'m now much more rooted in grief and alienation." Published by Loose Joints — editor Sarah Espanon pushed him away from the punchy, sarcastic pictures toward something more emotional and contemplative. "It\'s still me. It\'s just me in a way that I hadn\'t really bothered to see myself."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I have found a way to feel in love alone. To have the chemical experience of being in love alone."</div>'},
broskoski:{n:"Are.na / Charles Broskoski",d:"Technology",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Artist who gave up art to build a tool. "I decided making tools is the nicest thing you can do as an artist." Are.na — no algorithm, no likes, no push notifications. 15 years. 18,000 paying members. Two full-time employees. The slowest-growing platform on the internet, deliberately.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What drives him</div><p>The terror of missing the thing that matters. "What gives me anxiety is if there\'s a nodal point out there that I will never come across. What if \'the one\' is a piece of information that I will never get a chance to give my attention to?" He calls it "radar" — the ability to recognise when something belongs to you. Every platform around him is designed to dull that radar. Are.na exists to protect it.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The friction</div><p>A tech founder who refuses to play the tech game. No engagement optimisation. No growth hacking. No venture-scale ambition. Freelanced for years to keep Are.na alive without compromising it. "The Internet would be infinitely more interesting and healthy if there were just different takes towards what making a business online is." Aspires to become the next Nishiyama Onsen Keiunkan — a Japanese hot spring hotel founded in 705 AD. The patience isn\'t passive. It\'s a structural refusal to measure a tool for thinking in the language of scale.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The process</div><p>Collecting is thinking. Finds gathering references "infinitely pleasurable" and writing "excruciating." Goes back through his own channels like visiting a gallery — "it feels like all of that stuff is mine." Doesn\'t design by building and shipping. Designs by holding and looking. "The best thing is just feeling and holding stuff and looking at things until an idea comes around."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Childhood toy: a Spy Tools kit — black light, alarm system, fingerprinting kit. A kid who wanted to collect hidden information. First creative act: flipping ahead in the textbook to chapters that wouldn\'t be covered. "Part rebellion, but part just being interested." Self-described weakness: nostalgia — "my whole family is afflicted with this." Then del.icio.us died when Yahoo acquired it. The tool for intentional attention disappeared and nobody was building it back. Cory Arcangel was his professor — took him to Chelsea galleries, taught him to look at things as a game. The kid with the Spy Tools kit grew up and built the tool he\'d always needed.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Consider the possibility that working with your friends on something that you think is cool is the most luxurious possible thing that you can do."</div>'},
blazy:{n:"Matthieu Blazy",d:"Fashion · Bottega Veneta · Chanel",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Nearly 20 years invisible. Anonymous white coat at Margiela. Secret weapon at Raf Simons. Designed crystal-studded masks that became house emblems without anyone knowing his name. Gave up authorship over and over — the work was always attributed to others. When Bottega\'s creative director departed suddenly, the job fell to him. Then Chanel called. When the appointment went public, he panicked and hid in the south of Italy for 10 days. His title is Fashion Operation Director, not Creative Director — Chanel deliberately chose a different word.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What drives him</div><p>The work has to be true. He doesn\'t care if anyone knows it\'s him. 20 years of proof. At Chanel, he refused Lagerfeld\'s fitting room — "too charged with legacy and pressure" — and set up on the opposite side of the building. Went back past Karl to Coco herself. Found that the entire Chanel aesthetic came from practical circumstance, not vision from nowhere: discounted jersey from Rodier, burgundy linings because she could see her jewellery, men\'s tweed borrowed from a lover. "Perverse banality" — the ordinary remade so it looks identical but is completely transformed underneath. Found that the entire Chanel aesthetic came from practical circumstance, not vision from nowhere: discounted jersey from Rodier, burgundy linings because she could see her jewellery, men\'s tweed borrowed from a lover.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Cuts first, thinks after. On his first day at Chanel, he took a men\'s tweed sport coat and cut it into a Chanel jacket with scissors. "I might start with a suit, and by the end of the day it will become a dress. The first time I cut a piece — or a bag! — everyone was, well, not horrified, but surprised." Works in the round, Belgian style, scissors in hand. Communicates wordlessly with his research head Marie-Valentine Girbal — "at some point, we just got in sync."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Starts with the structure. First Haute Couture show at Chanel: stripped a tailleur down to its form — nothing left but the skeleton. The chain Coco Chanel once concealed inside hems, he left deliberately visible. Early looks in muslin — showing the construction before the finish. Then cuts into it. Day one at Chanel he took a men\'s tweed sport coat and cut it into a Chanel jacket with scissors. Works in the round, Belgian style, scissors in hand. "I might start with a suit, and by the end of the day it will become a dress. The first time I cut a piece — everyone was, well, not horrified, but surprised." Communicates wordlessly with his research head Marie-Valentine Girbal — "at some point, we just got in sync." Content dictates narrative, not image. Innovation operates not through rupture but through reordering priorities: method before signature, labour before image. Each model in the Couture show carried a personal element — a word or phrase discreetly embroidered, like a letter held in the hand.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The private life</div><p>Travels alone, often on foot. Prefers beer to champagne. Lackluster student sent to boarding school, then military school in Britain. When he got the biggest job in fashion, he moved into a flat he shares with his twin sister. Bought the house of the late sculptor Valentine Schlegel and is restoring it as a shared arts space. "It doesn\'t have to be perfect — it\'s a proposal."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"The more boundaries you have, the more freedom you can find in the small things."</div>'},
devlin:{n:"Es Devlin",d:"Stage Design",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes her unique</div><p>At 6, she saw a model of the town of Rye with lights that told folklore. "I believed that houses were the sight of stories." At 11, she stood in a music school corridor hearing Bach through one door and Miles Davis through another. "In some ways I see my practice as a 28-year extension of that corridor." Every project since is the same question: how does space hold narrative? The Super Bowl halftime show. The Lehman Trilogy. U2 at the Sphere in Las Vegas. The Olympics. A 900-page monograph and a Cooper Hewitt retrospective. From small theatres in 1995 to the largest LED screen on earth.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Partnership as method</div><p>She can\'t start without someone else\'s text. The practice structurally requires collaboration — Bono, Beyoncé, Benedict Cumberbatch, Brian Eno, Sam Mendes, Pharrell, Wire. Not decoration for their vision. Not her vision imposed on theirs. "My firm belief is that the text is in charge and that the design should serve the text." But inside that service she protects the right to make art. "I had a suspicion that one could serve the text and still be true to one\'s own sense of wanting to make a work of art." 28 years of proof that serving someone else\'s story is how her own work gets made.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Can\'t use the software herself. Her team prints it off and she sketches over it. Hires trained architects, not theatre designers. Views the audience as a temporary society. When stuck, sits among them. "I sit among the audience, and I feel it." Every project lives on the edge of being possible. "They\'re usually in that little space where people can\'t quite say they\'re impossible, but they wouldn\'t absolutely vouch for their possibility."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How she makes it</div><p>Gets a brief. Sleeps on it. Then gathers around the table with her team to talk. Keeps working on everything else — a train of thought already going in the studio can be the seed for the next thing. Keeps pieces of old models and sketches around as reference points, threading back to earlier trains of thought. Then drawing — sketching and looking up reference images. At the end of a session there\'ll be the beginnings of an idea. Her team starts to iterate, modelling quickly in 3D, creating sculptural studies that relate to her sketches. They keep checking in. She can\'t use the software herself — they print it off and she sketches over it. "I\'m still very old school. I just have a better day if I haven\'t spent all my time looking at a screen. If I want to communicate visually, it\'s hand drawn." When it becomes clear what\'s going to work, outside teams come in to build it. If something isn\'t working, she changes it. "As long as the thinking behind it is well rooted, you don\'t have to start again. Just remember what you\'re trying to say, and try to say it in a different language with different stuff." Hired 30 people from 500 applicants — all trained architects who\'d worked in music, fashion, film. The criteria: all the skills, but people she\'d want to have great conversations with every day. Her greatest teacher: her own humiliation. Sat next to her mum at a student show — "what\'s that hazy fuzzy thing meant to be?" "I won\'t forget that feeling. Being in touch with one\'s own memory of the last humiliation is a great driver for clarity."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Grew up in Rye, then Cranbrook, Kent. Art teacher took them into forests to build shelters and make sculptures. Set to continue at Saint Martins, then visited the Motley Theatre Design Course and changed everything. Ignored the stage directions from the start — "I didn\'t actually read that part." Hasn\'t developed an "Es Devlin style" — "so many of the choices I\'ve made were ingrained in me as a child."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"We\'re making things that are usually on the edge of being possible to make."</div>'},
escobedo:{n:"Frida Escobedo",d:"Architecture",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes her unique</div><p>Too shy for art. Chose architecture because "it seemed like something in which you had to express your personality, your feelings, your ideas, and I was too shy for that." Architecture was the safer place. Then made architecture that behaves like she does — recessive, layered, refusing to dominate. Too nervous to be an artist but too curious to be a traditional architect. The shyness wasn\'t overcome. It became the design principle.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What drives her</div><p>Curiosity, not vision. "I don\'t believe in specialisation, I prefer to do things for the first time." Embedded herself inside the Met for a year to redesign its modern wing — didn\'t design from the outside. Looks at things "through similarities rather than differences. Not chronological or geographical, but through similarities." Creativity is a muscle, but now curiosity has to do more with silence — "being able to be quiet rather than to feel excited. You need to calm down, slow down, and then be able to see things with different eyes."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>An exhibition on Emilio Ambasz she saw with her father at age seven. "White walls and a staircase that seemed to go up to nothing. After that, I understood that architecture could indeed be something super-utopian, imaginary." Applied for architecture almost by accident at 17 — it was the first deadline. Fell in love the first week — pulled an all-nighter that didn\'t feel painful. Still doesn\'t think she\'s good at it. "You\'re always trying to see if you\'re going to get better at it." Never worked for anyone. Opened her practice at 23. Built a house for a friend for less than $20,000.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The private self</div><p>An office of nine in Mexico City, now eleven in New York. No routine — "the routine thing is not a thing for me. It\'s always changing." Anchored by friends, family, walking alone in cities. Notices ruination — "what happens when things age and decay, become abandoned or fail. We should be planning for that." The identity she wants: not visionary, not bold. Curious.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Not a nostalgic continuation of the past but a search for layers of meaning that offer new perspectives on the present."</div>'},
field:{n:"Dylan Field / Figma",d:"Technology",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>One question: "What if design worked like Google Docs?" Dropped out of Brown at 20. Investor John Lilly turned down his seed round: "I don\'t think you know what you\'re doing yet." A Designer News commenter wrote: "If this is the future of design, I\'m changing careers." Built it anyway — free, in a browser, when the industry ran on expensive desktop software. Then watched what happened: people greeted each other on the canvas, typed to each other, played together. The tool became a place.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Partnership as structure</div><p>The product preaches collaboration. The founder had to be taught it. "I was just not a very good manager when I started Figma. I was an intern before that." His team staged a managerial intervention. He took a few days away. Came back different. "It\'s important to be vulnerable as a leader. It\'s important to share your struggles. Because people are looking to help and you\'re all together." Brian Collins wrote "Nothing great is made alone" for Figma\'s conference — but it describes the product itself. A tool whose entire purpose is making collaboration the default.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>Reads customer support tickets compulsively — not for praise but for the pulse. Visited users in Ukraine and Nigeria during the pandemic. "I spent most of the COVID-19 pandemic listening to Figma\'s users." Noticed that play matters as much as productivity — FigJam\'s cursor turns into a giant hand for high-fives. Designed serendipity into the tool on purpose: "It\'s really important to be intentional about creating serendipitous moments."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Penngrove, California. Father: respiratory therapist. Mother: resource specialist teacher. Named after Dylan Thomas. Child actor — fell asleep onstage in Peter Pan. Solved algebra at age 6, hung out with the school janitor because he was bored. "I don\'t know if I would\'ve invested in myself back then." Believes fear blocks compassion: "If I can figure out why I\'m being fearful, I can unblock that compassion."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"The more that you\'re visually creating, the less you\'re coming from a place of fear."</div>'},
fp:{n:"Floating Points / Sam Shepherd",d:"Music",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>PhD in the neuroscience of pain at UCL. Studies how the brain stores pain as memory. Then makes music that stores feeling as sound. The PhD wasn\'t preparation for music — it was the same act in a different register. "Hypothesizing is a creative process." The day after his PhD was finished, the switch flipped. "It was very clear, now I am a music person." Went to Marrakech the next day.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The outsider</div><p>A neuroscientist in the club. A Manchester kid in academia. Never done drugs in a culture built on them — "I never feel the need to take drugs to feel connected to the music, because I feel so connected already." Enters other people\'s traditions and finds the connection without flattening the difference. Collaborated with Pharoah Sanders at 81 — one take, no edits. Sanders died. The Hollywood Bowl memorial. Then Gnawa masters in Marrakech — "not being able to tap into what is so undeniably groovy knocked me out of my comfort zone." A ballet score for San Francisco Ballet. His biggest fear: fusion. Two traditions blended into something that respects neither.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>Deep listening, every day. "I wake up and put a record on, and I feel it." The listening never stops — "I\'m a zombie trying to fit the coffee thing together, but I\'ll be listening to Max Roach." Builds his own synthesizers and writes custom software to control them. Phoned the Buchla number 13 years ago — Don Buchla himself picked up and sent three modules. Accidentally wiped every preset on a Rhodes Chroma and started from scratch. A Sound Devices recorder runs constantly in the studio — "it listens to everything" — so he never interrupts the flow to hit record. Made Crush in five weeks to recapture the immediacy of his first EP at 17. Protects the naive against the sophisticated.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Almost everything starts with him playing the piano — a melody or chord sequence. Records it as one long audio file, one take. "Silhouettes" parts one, two and three are all one thing — one continuous take recorded on a computer. Then adds bass and drums himself. That becomes the demo. Then finds friends who can actually play the instruments. Has a rule: when he writes music out, he doesn\'t play it back on software. Plays it on the piano and figures it out as he goes. "You have to imagine it." Never studied audio engineering. "I don\'t know what I\'m doing in the studio, but I do know what I like the sound of." Listens to records thinking "that\'s amazing, I wonder how it\'s done" — then tries techniques out. Multitrack tape machines and synthesizers. Built a custom harmonograph to create the artwork for his record sleeves. A Sound Devices recorder runs constantly in the studio so he never interrupts the flow to hit record. Goes through months completely devoid of ideas. "That\'s totally normal. I\'m at a point where I\'m starting to become comfortable with not having ideas for a while." Phoned the Buchla number 13 years ago — Don Buchla himself picked up and sent three modules. Accidentally wiped every preset on a Rhodes Chroma and started from scratch. Made Crush in five weeks to recapture the immediacy of his first EP at 17.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Manchester. UK garage banging out of the pub across from his house. Teenage ritual of haunting record shops — his rare purchase would get a "Fucking hallelujah!" from the staff. Sent a mix CD to The End — thought Mr. C\'s callback was a mate winding him up. Warmed up for Andy C having never used a CDJ, ran out of records, played his own stuff. CD-R nights at Plastic People — producers sharing works in progress — became Eglo Records, became his whole world. Had 5,000 records, his girlfriend, and studio equipment all in his bedroom — "I had to crawl under the mixing desk to get into bed."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Pain is involved in so many things. The brain is in fact storing the pain as a memory."</div>'},
formafantasma:{n:"Formafantasma",d:"Design",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes them unique</div><p>They don\'t design objects. They design investigations. Ore Streams doesn\'t produce a chair — it produces a strategy for electronic waste, in conversation with recyclers, producers, lawmakers, and activists. Cambio doesn\'t produce furniture — it maps the entire timber extraction infrastructure. They gave up the output for the understanding. "We are not the type of designers that spend most of their time sketching forms — that is the last step."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What drives them</div><p>The wound isn\'t personal — it\'s the discipline itself. Design arose alongside industrial extraction and remains complicit in it. "Design is not only a solution but also part of the problem of the ecological crisis we find ourselves in." They protect the ability to say that — to hold the contradiction that design is both cause and potential cure. "Design is increasingly used as a marketing tool rather than a true design tool." They resist that at every level — giving up commercial practice for research and teaching. "We must become much more responsible and stop designing only for humans."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Research at a systemic scale, always. They need the whole supply chain visible before they\'ll design anything. Write about the work in the middle of the process — "to refine our thinking and identify any weaknesses." Writing as design tool. At the Serpentine, Cambio was "not only an exhibition but a way for us to show our approach, which goes beyond the design of the product." For Exposition Générale, they designed the exhibition apparatus itself — making the staging visible as a system.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How they make it</div><p>The research IS the design. Ore Streams: spent two years mapping the global electronic waste infrastructure before drawing anything. Visited recycling plants, interviewed lawmakers, tracked the journey of a discarded phone from a European bin to an informal dump in Ghana. Only then did they make objects — and the objects were arguments, not products. Cambio: mapped the entire timber extraction industry from forest to showroom. Commissioned scientific analysis of wood samples. The resulting exhibition at the Serpentine was the research made visible — not a display of designed things but a display of understanding. "We are not the type of designers that spend most of their time sketching forms — that is the last step." Write about the work in the middle of the process — "to refine our thinking and identify any weaknesses." Writing as design tool. For Exposition Générale at the Triennale, they designed the exhibition apparatus itself — the staging visible as a system, not hidden behind the work. The method is always the same: make the supply chain visible. See who profits and who suffers. Then — and only then — ask whether design should intervene, and how. Sometimes the answer is: don\'t make anything at all. Never start with the form or the medium — "it is always about what makes sense for a specific context." For Cassina\'s Staging Modernity: started with an image — what would happen if animals invaded the space of modernity? Commissioned three texts from an architect, a researcher, and a philosopher, blended by a theater director into a theatrical piece. Not celebration but critique. "Either the client is intelligent or they better just let you do the work."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The absence</div><p>Andrea Trimarchi and Simone Farresin. Both Italian, both left Italy. Met at Design Academy Eindhoven, now head its GEO-Design platform. Very private — interviews consistently focus on systems and materials, never personal history. The absence of personal voice is the data, like Philo\'s silence or The Row\'s refusal of press. They redirect every personal question toward the systemic. The person is deliberately absent so the research can be present.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"We need to understand that we as humans are part of nature. Nature is not something out there that we are manipulating. We are nature, and we are within it."</div>'},
fox:{n:"Toby Fox",d:"Gaming · Music",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Made Undertale — essentially alone. Wrote, designed, composed, and programmed it himself. An RPG where you could talk to every enemy instead of fighting them — and the game remembered what you chose, even across playthroughs. It made millions of players question the basic mechanic of every game they\'d ever played. Sold millions. Then made Deltarune the same way. Won\'t scale. Won\'t hire a team. In an industry of 500-person teams and $200 million budgets, he ships alone. Deliberately reclusive. "Apparently no one realized it was me, so I feel pretty good." Signs off every interview the same way: "Alright, see ya."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The friction</div><p>The original is sacred. Asked to compose replacement tracks for OFF\'s new soundtrack, he treated it as trespass: "Trying to replace those songs feels like breaking into somebody\'s house and pasting your face into their family photo album." Did the music for free. Will upload the tracks for free. Calls it "fanmusic" — made out of love and respect, not authorship. Won\'t claim what isn\'t his, even when he\'s the one making it. Six entirely different songs attempted. Every jazz song from the 1920s researched. Commissioned a fake jazz song just to sample it. The process IS the quality control — he doesn\'t release until it passes his own bar, even for free work.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Partnership (reluctant)</div><p>Couldn\'t crack the OFF battle theme alone. "I looked up almost every jazz song from the 1920s, I commissioned Carlos to make an entire fake jazz song for me so I could cut it up into samples, but nothing I could come up with on my own felt quite right." Then "summoned Camellia" to re-remix his track. The self-deprecation is the method: "Just feels like I got assigned to take a bullet in the back for everybody else." Even the most solo-authored practitioner in the project needed to let someone else in.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The position</div><p>The anonymity isn\'t avoidance — it\'s the creative stance. Like Philo, like The Row: disappear behind the work. Solo authorship as principle, but when the work requires collaboration, extreme humility. "What element are you?" "Meat."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Trying to replace those songs feels like breaking into somebody\'s house and pasting your face into their family photo album."</div>'},
gaggan:{n:"Gaggan Anand",d:"Food",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Wanted to be a drummer. Grew up penniless in Kolkata. "I always wanted to be a musician. I dreamt of being a professional drummer in a band, but one day, as a teenager, I realized that my economical situation would never improve pursuing my dream." The creative energy that couldn\'t go into music went into food. Then someone told him Indian food couldn\'t be fine dining. "Which pissed me off." Progressive Indian cuisine became the rebellion. A podcast about his life carries a suicide warning. More like a rock star than a chef.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What drives him</div><p>Negativity. "When somebody says no, I start saying yes. I need negativity to get challenged. It\'s the weirdness of my life. To be a hero you need a villain." Closed his restaurant at number one on the Asia\'s 50 Best list — "I don\'t want to be a monument." Reopened with 14 seats in Bangkok. The emoji menu removes the customer\'s ability to control the experience through words. Fighting on two fronts — against the West\'s reduction of Indian food and against Indian hospitality culture\'s own deference.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The outsider</div><p>Indian food was already molecular. "The whole texture and the taste is already in our country. We just need to exploit it." What the West called avant-garde, India had been doing with different words for centuries. Ferran Adrià at elBulli told him: "We want you to cook Indian food with our techniques." "My biggest rebellion was that I didn\'t want Indian cuisine to look like it\'s all naan, kulcha and biryani."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>The philosophy of the five Ss: sweet, sour, spicy, salty, and surprise. A simple bite might be made by eight or ten different kitchen hands through a process that takes a week — but when you eat it, it\'s just one bite. "When you can have something so good for such a short time, you want more, but you can\'t get it." Started with a purple ingredient in the kitchen — asked diners how many purple ingredients they could name. Most said a few. There are nearly 40. Shaped them into a purple heart served to Prince\'s Purple Rain. "People listen to Purple Rain and eat the dish and they are in the zone." A menu is like a music album — each course a song, the journey takes you through the ups and downs. Half a crab sashimi with coconut ice cream and half a cooked crab curry — both from the same crab leg. Half cooked, half raw. "How is that possible? It\'s impossible. So we exploit the impossible and make it into a dish." The baked rice: 54 individual portions, one per diner per sitting. 40 grams of rice, 40ml of stock, finished exactly one minute before being served. Hired four chefs to work on rice alone. "No restaurant in the world cooks rice individually. That\'s how perfection can be achieved." The emoji menu removes the customer\'s ability to control the experience through words. 25 handmade menu pieces that together make up the floorplan of the restaurant — made by a 70-year-old artisan he met and employed. Now working with a neurologist to map the taste journey. When food touches the lips: spice first, then sweet — the brain likes this most. Then salt, then bitterness. On the tongue: sourness, and at the centre is umami where all the tastes pull together. Temperature and texture connect mouth and tongue simultaneously. "Like striking several chords on a piano to make the perfect sound." Lick It Up: three sauces that work backwards on the taste theory — acidity of tomatoes at the bottom, saltiness of peas and mushrooms in the middle, spice on top. Lick from bottom to top. Kiss plays loud in the restaurant. "Chefs are like rock stars and the guests want a show." Yogurt Explosion — the first dish, still served as amuse bouche: mango chutney in a spherified yogurt bomb. Reverse spherification learned from Ferran Adriá\'s olive technique at El Bulli. "Total umami — this is my life work and my Mona Lisa. I will achieve this before I die."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Got drunk one night in September 2009 and called a friend: "I\'m doing a restaurant." Within a week he\'d resigned. "Everyone asked if I was mad. They said a concept like that will be a Titanic." His team of 65 defied poaching attempts from his former partners — "one of the most powerful moments of my life." As a child, he and his father would get fresh produce and create a menu together. The ritual started there. Buddhist impermanence as menu philosophy — nothing stays, everything changes. "When I cook, I forget about being sad or happy — I\'m in my own world." Cooking is meditation, not production.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"To be a hero you need a villain."</div>'},
ghotmeh:{n:"Lina Ghotmeh",d:"Architecture",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes her unique</div><p>Grew up in Beirut during the civil war, watching her mother submit her architecture diploma during on-off bombing. "Creativity was the place where one could unleash, imagine, dream of another world." Left for Paris in 2006. Won the Estonian National Museum competition at 26 — arrived without an office, handed the jury a business card, and realised she should bring someone with grey hair next time. "I grew up in Lebanon. Nothing is given to you and no government. You have to learn to survive and to just do things and dream, and make them happen."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The resistance</div><p>Every project resists something. The Estonian Museum resists occupation — built on a Soviet military airfield the brief tried to ignore, transforming a scar into a threshold. Stone Garden resists amnesia — Beirut\'s habit of erasing its war scars before anyone can grieve. Its hand-combed concrete façade survived the 2020 port explosion. The Hermès workshop resists the idea that industrial buildings have to be ugly — 500,000 handmade bricks, first low-carbon energy-positive industrial building in France. "Within this, there is a certain modes of resilience or resistance. And maybe through different projects, there is a sense of what I grew up with in Beirut."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>Archaeology as method, every time. Look at the ground. Research what was there. Find the material locally. Bring the community into the making. At Hermès, the brickmakers hadn\'t built a full structure in years — she found a master mason to retrain them. "They were proud to master this technique. That act of building becomes an act of love." Insists on managing construction sites herself: "If you\'re not managing the site, the manager will tell you it\'s not possible." While excavating for Hermès, discovered a 16,000-year-old Magdalenian tool-making site. The client said: "That\'s your fault. Archaeology of the future."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What she notices</div><p>The boundary between a window and a wound. "In Beirut, the boundary between an articulated window, the memory of a violent event is constantly blurred." Violence and architecture share the same marks on a building\'s skin. And: "Creativity is about this moment of stillness that we need to be together."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I like it when something very simple can evoke so many different layers of meaning and memory."</div>'},
joseph:{n:"Kahlil Joseph",d:"Film",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Asked to discuss himself at a public event, he said "No" stone-faced. The packed room erupted with nervous laughter. Notorious for not doing press. The work speaks; the person doesn\'t. Creates intellectually and emotionally dense short films — for Kendrick Lamar, Beyoncé, Sampha, FKA twigs — but resists every frame of conventional filmmaking. "I\'m obsessed with Blackness. The diversity of it is astounding."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What drives him</div><p>The absent archive. BLKNWS — his ongoing project shown at Venice Biennale and MoMA — is "conceptual journalism": what if news encompassed anything from the past or present, as long as it was revelatory? He builds the record that doesn\'t exist. "Filmmakers don\'t ever go as far as they should with sound." The density is the point — every frame carries more than it should be able to hold.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Partnership as structure</div><p>Editor-in-chief, not auteur. The BLKNWS feature film had four directors — Garrett Bradley, Raven Jackson, Arthur Jafa, Kaneza Schaal — and two cinematographers. "Singularity of vision and porous collaboration are not in opposition. They are, in fact, intrinsically connected. People in film like to lie about it." Collaborators function like jazz musicians — editor Luke Lynch describes "moments where I fell into the pocket and executed something I couldn\'t ever write or do on purpose outside of that moment."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>Listening. "It\'s generally bigger than me. A conversation happens and then like eight weeks later… here we are. I just try to listen." No one gave him big budgets, so he started making $5-10K videos. The constraint became the method — and never left. The density of every frame comes from not having resources to be wasteful.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Born Seattle, 1981. Younger brother Noah Davis was a painter and museum curator who co-founded The Underground Museum in LA. Noah died young. Kahlil became its artistic director — carrying a practice that belonged to someone who was lost. Influenced by Roy DeCarava since before everything he\'s ever made. "I\'m interested in authenticity, period. When you meet Kendrick it matches up with who he is on CD."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Singularity of vision and porous collaboration are not in opposition. People in film like to lie about it."</div>'},
kouthoofd:{n:"Jesper Kouthoofd / Teenage Engineering",d:"Technology · Product",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Father was a Dutch architect who drew beautifully but couldn\'t sell. Mother was a Swedish banker. "I got 50/50." Slept under his father\'s drawing desk as a child. Grew up borrowing instruments from his brother\'s music store every weekend — a four-track recorder, some Boss pedals, a drum machine, a Japanese synth, all in a backpack. "If you look at the OP-1, it\'s actually exactly those parts I had in my backpack." He designs from autobiographical need, not market research.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What drives him</div><p>Restriction as freedom. RAL colors — a 40-color scale — because Pantone has too many blues. Simple geometric shapes. German industrial standards. Triangle is always yellow, square is blue, circle is red. No capital letters — "democratic — why should certain words have more meaning?" He sticks to rules to become free again. Single-brain design — "I\'m the only one allowed to do design." No user testing. "We really don\'t care if the audience likes it. It\'s important to us." Told Volvo their design department is actually a styling department. "They got super upset and kicked us out of the project. But it was worth it."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>Rehearses organ every night for five years — to design one. "I\'m super bad. I\'m not musical. But I really need to understand what makes an organ an organ." Bought a CNC machine and learned CAD from scratch. Makes manifestos as books in 72-hour sprints. "If you are a creative person, you don\'t have to be stuck in one medium. When I design a product, it\'s like making a film. You tell a story." The making IS the understanding. You can\'t design what you haven\'t held. It\'s about muscle memory — "the experiences you had when you were young. Maybe you turned a knob or did something with your hands that you never forgot." Physical touch as design principle.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Single-brain operation. "I\'m the only one allowed to do design." Design team of eight to ten people — "please Jesper, can I do some design now? No, you\'re not ready yet." Told a young designer to make a musical keyboard. The designer started drawing. "You need to know how to play the instrument before you design it." So he sits every night for one to two hours rehearsing a classical organ with pedals. Five years now. "I\'m super bad. I\'m not musical. But I really need to understand what makes an organ an organ." The OP-1 started as a choice between a synthesizer and a clock radio. Four guys — two software, one learned electronics from scratch. He learned CAD from scratch on Ashlar Vellum. "That was the fun part — we learned over time while we were building." Still works with pen and markers. Makes manifesto books in 72-hour sprints — all the images and ideas in one book, sent to the print shop, back in three days. The Nothing phone started as a sketch on the back — he flipped it over and started drawing on the side without the display. The first sketch became the final design. No user testing. "We really don\'t care if the audience likes it. It\'s important to us."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Sinclair ZX81 at age 11. "That started my whole career. I discovered that limitations actually spark your creativity." Made record sleeves at 15. Founded ACNE, left when "this is done." Directed commercials for 20 years — "I was a prostitute." Couldn\'t be employed anywhere. "I really had to create my own space because I couldn\'t be employed anywhere else. I don\'t know why." Virgil Abloh knocked on the door in Stockholm. "I\'m shy and he was also a little bit shy. We connected in that way. We both liked to discover things with our hands." Built a DJ deck in two months. "We became friends and I miss him a lot."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Good design doesn\'t have to be beautiful. It has to be personal."</div>'},
loosejoints:{n:"Loose Joints / Lewis Chaplin & Sarah Piegay Espenon",d:"Publishing",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes them unique</div><p>A couple who became a publishing house. Lewis studied anthropology — drawn to projects that use something specific and intimate as an allegory for broader stories. Sarah studied fine art and design. First project: a 12-page Richard McGuire comic they emailed him about off the cuff. Now one of the most respected photobook publishers in the world — Daniel Arnold, Jack Davison, Harley Weir, Bobby Doherty. Anti-house-style as philosophy: "In an ideal world, people wouldn\'t look at any of our books and immediately tell it\'s made by Loose Joints."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>Patience as method. Sophie Green\'s Congregation took nearly two years from first edit to publication. "We never choose to rush a project — even if the artist wants to — if we think it needs more work." They see what artists make when no one\'s looking. Convinced Bobby Doherty to publish four years of private photographs. Found Robin Graubard — a photojournalist in her 70s who covered the fall of communism across Yugoslavia. Never published a book. Sarah spotted a handful of photos online and reached out. "Incredible work, most of which has barely seen the light of day." 120 submissions a month, reviewed every one. "We like it when we can see a great spark of an idea and then we can get involved."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Partnership</div><p>Complementary, not identical. "Sarah\'s better at editing and sequencing. She has design ideas that are sometimes more ambitious than mine. I do the technical stuff, layout, print production, logistics." Sarah pushes toward complicated-but-special. Lewis knows how to make things easier but lets her ambition override convenience. "That\'s a good, productive tension." Every artist collaboration is different — some hand over a hard drive, some arrive with a near-finished dummy, some make the book and the work simultaneously.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How they make it</div><p>Bring artists to the atelier in Marseille, often with no predefined idea of the book before they arrive. Start with a blank document. Spend days in the studio discussing the intention of the work. Then editing, sequencing, thinking, choosing, trying things out — arriving together at a first draft, design direction, format, materials. Sarah is creative director and editor — her ideas shape the edit, sequence, and creative direction. Lewis works in parallel on the conceptual, graphic, technical, and reprographic sides. "All the different processes of the book are interlinked." Always make the covers last — so they absorb everything that came before. Some artists have clearly defined ideas. Others bring tens of thousands of images and need help finding the form. Every tiny choice about the book\'s material and graphic qualities is stress-tested to ensure it means something in relation to the narrative. "What happens to photography when you put it on the page?" Lewis\'s background in anthropology — how a specific story can use photography to speak broadly about wider human experience. Disco and funk while editing. Jon Hassell in the background. Studio in the apartment in Marseille, striking distance from la Bonne Mère. "Allow your thoughts to change direction. Trust in the you of now. Generously borrow from those who have come before you. Don\'t rush anything."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The friction</div><p>Left London for Marseille after Brexit destroyed their European economics. Traded proximity for freedom. Opened Ensemble — a bookshop and gallery in Marseille, all furniture on wheels so the space can transform. The publishing house became a physical place. Freelance design on the side to fund ambitious publishing. Use only recycled or FSC-certified papers. Stopped flying. "Knowing that what you love is directly something that extracts natural resources from an already fragile ecosystem." Fear complacency most.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Satisfying our own whim and curiosity. And maybe that\'s still what it is now as well."</div>'},
mschf:{n:"MSCHF / Gabe Whaley",d:"Art · Product",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes them unique</div><p>"Can we make a company that is an artist?" That\'s the question. Not an art collective — "nobody really knows what that means." They see every system as material to be reverse-engineered: the legal system, the art market, the sneaker economy, the viral loop. Satan Shoes, Big Red Boots, the $76,000 Birkin cut into four sandals. "Not so much the future as it is the absurd intensification of the present moment." Built 300 websites because "there\'s a flattening effect for everything that passes through platforms." Been kicked off Venmo, banned by T-Mobile.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The outsider</div><p>Founder Gabe Whaley grew up in rural North Carolina. Immigrant Korean mother. Father in the army. No TV, no movies, no video games, no popular music. Slightly above-average student, decent classical pianist. Got into West Point — spent two years there, then dropped out at 20. "Imagine leaving a cult that you were in your entire life and then popping up in New York City for the first time ever." Spent three years trying to figure out where he belonged. "I created these projects that critiqued everything I was observing because I wasn\'t able to participate in it." The team is built in the same image: "Quiet nerds who love making things."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>Daily brainstorms — Monday through Friday, one hour, no exceptions. "Being creative is actually a muscle. If you go for long periods without stretching your brain, you do get worse at it." One person\'s full-time job is librarian — building a collegiate curriculum of inputs. The whiteboard behind them: toilets, Eva and Franco Mattes, large-scale land-based. The subway is mandatory — "it creates tension, and out of that tension come new ideas." The studio\'s shared language works like jazz — people who\'ve never collaborated before can play together because they speak the same creative language. Most common feedback: "Can we make it shittier?" Good design no one remembers. Shitty design they never forget. Celebrate the night before something launches, never after. "Celebrate the act of creation, not the response."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How they make it</div><p>Daily brainstorms — Monday through Friday, one hour, no exceptions. "Being creative is actually a muscle. If you go for long periods without stretching your brain, you get worse at it." One person\'s full-time job is librarian — building a collegiate curriculum of inputs. The whiteboard behind them: toilets, Eva and Franco Mattes, large-scale land-based. The subway is mandatory — "it creates tension, and out of that tension come new ideas." Most common feedback: "Can we make it shittier?" Good design no one remembers. Shitty design they never forget. Projects operate on one to three year timelines even though they drop weeks apart. "It\'s always funny when someone says, oh, you started that project when the previous one ended? No, that would be impossible." Outrage is never the genesis. "I can\'t remember a time where going after a certain company or trying to elicit a certain response was the genesis of a project. We wanted this thing to exist. If the result is legal action, it\'s a risk we\'re willing to take." Distribution is part of the concept from the beginning — not something figured out after. "How things live, how people interact with them is integral to what we\'re making." Key4All: a single 2004 PT Cruiser with 5,000 keys sold for $18 each. Anyone who found the car could drive it. They thought it would crash in two days. It was on the road for nine months. The performance was conducted by the 5,000 people, not MSCHF. Celebrate the night before something launches, never after. "Celebrate the act of creation, not the response."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The friction</div><p>They critique consumerism while deriving revenue from consumer impulses. The paradox is acknowledged, not resolved. "We would go viral and it felt amazing. Then, after enough times, you feel nothing." The two-week drops are done. "Instead of 40 to 50 new things a year, we might do three, maybe five. And you might not even know they were us." A TikTok of their Tokyo show got 30 million views. Whaley felt nothing. But the 3,000 people in the room felt significant. "It would be better if it never even made it on social media. Just let these 3,000 people cherish this forever." They now have a theme parks division. The internet collective is looking for walls.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Humor is one of the best tools to get people to engage in subject matter they\'d otherwise be afraid of."</div>'},
nerihu:{n:"Neri&Hu",d:"Architecture",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes them unique</div><p>Met at the same church growing up. Married in 1992. Both worked for Michael Graves. Moved to Shanghai by accident — a three-month project became a year, then a life. "Everyone thought we were really smart. Trust me, we were just naive, young, fearless." Rossana\'s father was from Shanghai — "I felt like coming full circle." Now 110 people, 30 languages, but "we don\'t act like a corporate practice. We are actually many different small studios in a big practice."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Partnership as structure</div><p>Lyndon is better at concept stage and drawing. Rossana at development stage and words. "A lot of architectural practices are shared by husband-and-wife teams — maybe the demands of work make it only possible that we work together to stay married." Lyndon wanted to be a painter — switched to architecture to reconcile passion with his father\'s "Asian pragmatic realism." Rossana took five years off to be a full-time mother. "Totally crazy, but it makes me value work because I realised working is so much easier than being at home." Lyndon reads Susan Sontag "to understand my wife."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What drives them</div><p>Heritage against demolition. Shanghai as palimpsest — "you can see the influx of both the influence, and at the same time the resistance, to many of these influences." Their practice is fundamentally about adaptive reuse — saving buildings that don\'t have the preservation plaque. "The client wanted us to demolish. But we went on site and said, you know what? This is actually much more interesting." The method repeats: go to the site first, research from all directions, look for traces and signs. "We are very much inspired by the everyday, the mundane, and the ordinary." Interviewed 50 architects practicing in Shanghai and compiled Persistence of Vision — "when people have a platform for dialogue and discourse, people become better." Saint-Exupéry: "We don\'t ask to be eternal beings, but we ask that things do not lose all their meaning."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The private life</div><p>Their house has never been published despite requests from AR and AD. Secret garden with trees taller than houses and scattered renovated ruined outbuildings. Rossana grew up in Taiwan with no toys — played on the streets and hunted unusual metal scraps. Lyndon paints. "It\'s hard to find our house, but we have had encounters."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"It\'s never about style. It\'s never about a look. It should always be about meaning."</div>'},
papaioannou:{n:"Dimitris Papaioannou",d:"Performance",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>A painter who left painting because he was alone. "I do theatre because I must be with other people. I was once a painter — my painting is stronger than my theatre — but I was alone." Makes silent theater — no text, no recorded sound. The audience and the body must be in the same room. Not discovered internationally until 50. Directed the 2004 Athens Olympics opening ceremony. Self-described introvert who makes work for crowds.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The outsider</div><p>Co-edited openly gay countercultural zines in 1980s Greece. Ran away at 18. A painter who became a comics artist who became a performer — "as a painter, this was the place to create images; as a comics artist, this was where to tell my tales; and as a performer, this was the context in which to present myself." All disciplines are one act. Every move stripped away one more thing until only the body remained.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>The body IS the medium. Silent theater — images not words. Returns constantly to Greek myths. "Sisyphus is like a working class hero." Camus, work as meaning. "Still Life is a work about work." Long-term ensembles — international auditions, then months of rehearsal in Athens. "Talented people are willing to leave their homes and take an apartment in Athens in order to work with me." The collaboration requires relocation.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The private life</div><p>Parents bring homemade food weekly. Sketches at nudist beaches. The paradox of a private person who makes the most public art form — performance for thousands. "I\'m primarily a painter. I try to compose images." The painting never stopped. It just found a different surface.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I do theatre because I must be with other people. I was once a painter — my painting is stronger than my theatre — but I was alone."</div>'},
satisfy:{n:"Brice Partouche / Satisfy",d:"Product · Running",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Designed the complete first collection in his head while running. "My best ideas come to me when I run. Maybe because during a run you settle into the natural or innate \'you\' and then your mindstate becomes the way it should be." The creative practice and the business are the same activity. "We\'re like a band. Satisfy.com — that\'s the merch table. But the merch is super technical, super premium. And the experience is running."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What drives him</div><p>The refusal of score culture. Came from skateboarding and punk where there\'s no score. Found running culture\'s obsession with performance alienating. "Running was not about performance at all for me." Running in the sixties — girls weren\'t even allowed to run. "That\'s one of the things I really value in running, for me it still represents rebellion. Similar to skateboarding and surfing." The sacred morning run alone: "It\'s not being anti-social — it\'s an opportunity to be with yourself."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>Nine people. Pattern maker Kotaro spends up to a week constructing a single pair of shorts. Everything developed in-house. Noticed French silk factories that had converted to technical fibers — "extremely good and premium fabric mills" that nobody in running was using. The first Satisfy short was designed from frustration: phone bouncing, keys jingling. Double belt, hidden carabiner, membrane pocket. "I\'m a great leader. I\'m a terrible manager." Owns Ob-La-Di café in Paris where runners gather. At Pitti Uomo in Florence, "all the guys meet at the crack of dawn on Ponte Vecchio."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>It all starts with the fabric. Goes to Première Vision and Performance Days like going to a concert. Noticed French silk factories that had pivoted to technical fibers when silk production moved to Asia — "extremely good and premium fabric mills" that nobody in running was using. Developed Justice™, one of the lightest woven fabrics in the world, in France. "Your first interaction with any product is the feel and the weight. A tactile experience that precedes anything else." Groups all fabrics under Peace and Silence Technology — peace to the body, no noise in motion. MothTech™: laser-cut holes in cotton T-shirts where the body needs ventilation — came from him wearing super distressed band tees. CloudMerino™: the thinnest merino in the world, knitted in Japan, hand-dyed following the Shibori method. Raw hems everywhere — "you just add distraction, thickness, and rub." Designed the first collection in his head while running. Within two weekends, he and Kotaro created most of the brand\'s current styles. First short from frustration: phone bouncing, keys jingling. Double belt, hidden carabiner, membrane pocket. Kotaro spends a week on a single pair. No collections, no overproduction, no sales. "If you sell a pair of shorts for $40, there is a problem." Compares the online store to a merch table — "buying a souvenir from an experience." When he has to run 10K at 5 minutes per kilometre, he puts on Powerslave by Iron Maiden — "I know it is exactly 50 minutes."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Grenoble, Alps region. Father had a denim brand in the \'80s — flea markets together, material knowledge inherited. Played drums in heavy metal and hardcore bands. Failed medical school. Made skinny jeans for 17 years — also a music label, seven-inch records, several bands. "I\'m just bored with my jeans company and I love running so much." Each departure a reinvention. "Unlike animals, we can reinvent ourselves. A dog will always be a dog. But we can become whatever we want to become."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"The problem is not that Satisfy shorts are $200. The problem is that some shorts are $40. How can you make a short at $40? There\'s a catch."</div>'},
perplexity:{n:"Perplexity / Escha Vera",d:"Technology · Design",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes her unique</div><p>A musician and artist who designs products. Runs a record label. Makes art. Lone wolf her entire career — sole designer at Microsoft (helped establish Metro), OpenTable, Detour, Descript, now Perplexity. "I\'ve just been alone for so long that I didn\'t actually have designers to riff on." Built design systems since 2008. The muscle was built in isolation. At Perplexity, brand team and product team separated by "a waist-high wall" — constant collaboration across it.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What drives her</div><p>A moral obligation to stay. Left Descript after seven years and "felt like maybe my career is over." Spent a year talking to CEOs — "either I got bad answers to questions about AI ethics, or they didn\'t have answers. And that made me uncomfortable." Chose to stay in AI rather than walk away. "I couldn\'t live with exiting the scene and watching it go down a path I wasn\'t comfortable with that I knew I could have had an impact on."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>First day at Perplexity — no design system. Built one from scratch. Fought the chat interface as default — "it\'s an engineering approach, a headless UI. It leads to a blinking cursor problem." At Descript, productized AI without calling it AI — sliders and dropdowns instead of prompts, building the prompt invisibly in the background. The workflow IS the practice: Figma to Claude to Cursor to Photoshop to MidJourney to custom-trained models, constantly feeding outputs back as inputs. "Anything I\'ve ever shared has hundreds of parents that led to that result." Made the Comet onboarding feel like starting up a Nintendo 64. The track: "Waking Up Before Everyone Else at the Sleepover, and the Wii is Still On." Uses AI like an artist, not a slot machine. "It\'s not about how little can you do. It\'s about how much more can you do."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The tension</div><p>Perplexity\'s citation system is a design choice — this is fact, this is source, this is how we know. "The orchestration is the product. The model is a tool." But the copyright controversies complicate everything. She\'s the authored practice inside that unresolved tension — the designer who cares about ethics building the product that tests where those ethics land.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"How do you craft an experience that makes people feel something? AI is so early. We\'re figuring out the patterns."</div>'},
perron:{n:"Willo Perron",d:"Stage Design · Furniture",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Dropped out of performing arts high school at 14. Ran a record shop and rap label in Montreal. Designed every American Apparel store. Designed stadium tours for Kanye, Beyoncé, Rihanna\'s Super Bowl. Designed Chanel\'s runway — a giant black ribbon curling toward the ceiling of the Grand Palais. Now furniture for Knoll. Never trained in any of it. The method is always the same: take a simple idea and blow it up to its most extreme. Canal Street slat walls become American Apparel. A cushion becomes a sofa system for Knoll. Silver Lake studio — miniature arena sets on the second floor. "There\'s a playfulness. It\'s a kid\'s thing. I could stare at these little replicas all day long." Wallpaper* Designer of the Year 2026.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The outsider</div><p>Post-referendum Montreal in the mid-\'90s — exodus of people and money, "kind of like Berlin after the wall came down. We grew up with a lot of space and no resources. It forced you to become creative." Culture hadn\'t fused yet — punk kids, club scene, skateboarders, all separate. He crossed every world alone. Met Kanye through A-Trak in Kuala Lumpur on a sabbatical in Asia. "I felt such a sense of relief" — finally someone else who crossed all the worlds at once. Chose anonymity for two decades. Left American Apparel when burnt out. Left Apple. Eventually separated from Kanye. Split with business partner Roettinger. Each departure clean. "It happened when it was supposed to happen."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What drives him</div><p>Confluence. "For me it\'s really about the confluence of things that becomes interesting." And imperfection — "the gap tooth or the scar are the things that give you personality. Perfect beauty always seems like a trick." Needs argument: "I like mistakes. I like arguing with people." "Difficult people make beautiful things." Now restless again — wellness pavilions, furniture for sex, transportation design. "There\'s no five- or ten-year plan. It\'s more about finding opportunities to do what I haven\'t already done."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Father was a jazz pianist. Brother an interior designer. Montreal childhood of hip-hop and museums. "Intellectual competitiveness where nobody will ever admit to competing." "Furniture has always felt like the thing I was meant to do" — but it took 20 years of stage design before the first collection.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I believe in broadcast — success stories are the ones where something great gets done in a big way without compromise."</div>'},
seals:{n:"Tré Seals / Vocal Type",d:"Type Design",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Protest signs were never meant to last longer than a day. He makes them last forever — extracting typefaces from the hand-painted letters on banners and posters, turning tools of resistance into tools of design. Founded Vocal Type to fight stereo-typography — the "chop suey" fonts for East Asian restaurants, the heavy-weight fonts used for stories about Black people. "The letters that make words should also have power." 80% self-taught. Forbes 30 Under 30. Spike Lee commissioned the book SPIKE.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Brain tumors at age 4. Drawing and cursive as pain relief — "it relaxed me and made all the pain and fear and everything go away." Montessori school that only taught cursive — "cursive became like drawing squiggly lines and doing work at the same time." Graffiti names on index cards for $3 in fifth grade. The hand that drew through illness became the hand that designs typefaces. Great-great-grandfather was a carpenter and mason — built the family home in 1908 using materials from the land. Great-great-grandmother ran the farm, ran a boarding house for teachers, was the bank to the Black community, sold 2,000 acres to local Black families so they could establish their own legacy.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The outsider</div><p>Nine out of ten jobs, the only person of colour in the office. "The only time I got to communicate with people outside the office was behind the lunch counter at the restaurant next door." 3-3.5% of all practicing designers in America are Black. Then George Floyd. "We went from 3,000 to 12,000 followers in a month." Feared his success came from tragedy — "every opportunity I received was not because of my talent. It was because of George." Busiest months for five years: Black History Month and Juneteenth. "We\'re hired based on the months we\'re in." Fighting to break out of that mould.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>25% research, 25% design, 25% research, 25% design. Starts by identifying an activist or a movement — ties the activist to the movement or the movement to a particular activist. Scales down to specific protests. Finds typographic references that multiple people have a connection with — never one protest sign made by one person. Usually one sign that 400 or 500 people carried, or a banner that 10 or 20 held. Unity, not individual authorship. The second round of research catches what the first missed — another source that informs characters he didn\'t have before, because with a revival you never have the entire alphabet. Starts by scribbling until he gets the feel of the letter versus how it should look. Overlays those scribbles until the end result emerges. Always starts with a lowercase n — 80% of the lowercase alphabet is built from the construction of a lowercase n. "Flip it, raise it, cut it, rotate it." From n you get a. From uppercase H and O you get the majority of uppercase components. The S is one of the hardest characters — and the ampersand. The Martin typeface: before Dr. King arrived, most signs at the Memphis sanitation strike were stenciled — everyone got the same stencils from the same hardware store, or they were passed around. "It speaks to people\'s economic status and what resources they had access to." Ruby: remaking a font called Jim Crow — stolen from a French foundry, renamed by American Type Founders in 1933. Renaming it after Ruby Bridges, the first child to integrate schools in the South.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>Works from a refurbished chicken coop on the family farm in Accokeek, Maryland. Parents\' office next door — they still do invoicing on a typewriter. Ancestry room with portraits from the 1800s. 80% of the lowercase alphabet is built from the construction of a lowercase N — "flip it, raise it, cut it, rotate it." "A beautiful collection of letters, not a collection of beautiful letters." Every typeface starts from a reference image — a protest banner, a campaign poster — then traces the movement, the activist, the history. Three starting points, same destination.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"What does it look like to take this tool that was never meant to last more than a day and make it a tool that can last forever?"</div>'},
toogood:{n:"Faye Toogood",d:"Design · Furniture · Fashion",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes her unique</div><p>Studied fine art and art history, not design. "Winning Designer of the Year — maybe now I can finally call myself a designer." Spent eight years as interiors editor at World of Interiors — travelled to Rajasthan, Swedish castles, mud huts in Mali. Then the two-dimensional page wasn\'t enough. Started her studio on a kitchen table. Tom Dixon told her to stop throwing things in the bin and start making things permanent. Now furniture, clothing with her sister Erica, interiors, sculpture — across all of it, the same instinct: architecture for the body.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The friction</div><p>Twenty years ago, cut her hair off, removed all colour and decoration from her work, worked only in steel and welding. "I genuinely felt that was the only way I was going to be taken seriously." Refused all interviews about being female in design. No work in any UK museum. America took her with gusto. Now, twenty years later: "the colour, the decoration can flood back into my work." Against the computer — encourages her studio to close them. Against the phone — "I am so frightened for the next generation." Against overproduction — "we can\'t keep up with this pace. We need to make less." Against global shipping — "this whole way of working is going to have to change."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>Everything starts small. Canvas, paper, wire — a childlike palette. Makes maquettes by hand, never on the computer. "I have to take away everything and go back into a play-like state." Describes herself as a barometer — "a thermometer to the world. Design doesn\'t come from repeating references. It comes from feeling what\'s going on." The moment of creation has to be captured in the finished object — "if something gets overdeveloped, you lose that very moment." The Roly Poly chair walks into the room before she does. A studio of 25 Misfits from different disciplines. No office, no desk. "I know they\'ve been working if it\'s messy."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How she makes it</div><p>Starts by taking everything away. Canvas, paper, wire — a childlike palette. Makes maquettes by hand, never on the computer. "I have to take away everything and go back into a play-like state." The moment of creation has to be captured in the finished object — "if something gets overdeveloped, you lose that very moment." Her Manufracture exhibition at Stockholm showed prototypes, things that didn\'t work, half-made pieces — "showing the vulnerability of the designer and how many years it takes to get something off the ground, how many failures before a success." Tom Dixon told her to stop throwing things in the bin. That was the turn. Worked only in steel and welding for twenty years to be taken seriously. Removed colour, pattern, anything decorative. Now the colour floods back. "Surely AI will be able to design a better Faye Toogood chair than Faye Toogood. What can I bring? Humanity and emotion." No desk in the studio. Knows the team have been working if it\'s messy. Designers who join haven\'t studied anything pre-1910 — she insists they look back. On pricing: "We understand the difference between a £2.99 chicken and a £15 chicken. But somehow we can\'t make that connection with furniture."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Grew up in the middle of nowhere, foraging objects in the countryside. No television. Books, museums, family culture. Designers who join her studio haven\'t studied anything pre-1910. She insists they look back. "Those are human reference points." Now moving into the second half — natural materials only, no chemicals. Head, heart, hands, making, body — "all of these things are very much connected." Wants to design a playground.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"A successful design has that very moment of creation captured within it. That is the magic bit that connects you."</div>'},
tyler:{n:"Tyler, the Creator",d:"Music · Fashion · Media",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Every album creates a total environment — music, fashion, stage design, colour palette, typography, everything integrated. "There\'s no difference between the windows at the Golf store and a piano interlude on Igor." At 7, sat in front of speakers listening to Brandy and Sade — heard music as weather before he had words for it. "I love when it slants. The cloud, the cloud, it slants!" Last four albums all No. 1 on Billboard 200. Don\'t Tap the Glass — written backstage on tour — is a joyful journey through a half-century of Black dance music. The archive is the resource. Feature film debut in Safdie\'s Marty Supreme. Never done drugs. Always smiling. Keeps a dream diary. Goes shopping in Paris reading from it. Biked to Manhattan Beach as a kid, scrawling lyrics on his pants with a marker. The practice hasn\'t changed — just the scale.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The outsider</div><p>At 9, bought a Jamiroquai album and couldn\'t play it for other kids. Never met his father — "Bastard," his first album title. Mother raised him in Hawthorne, South LA. Odd Future was the anti-gang — less a crew than a collective. Boyce, Frank Ocean, Syd, Earl Sweatshirt, each with their own vision. Tyler\'s was the loudest voice but never alone. Boyce: "He had a very distinct sense of humor that I understood. But there were kids who didn\'t get it. The point of it is not to be got. That\'s always been his baseline." Theresa May banned him from Britain for his lyrics. "I was always the one that would jump in front of the bus to make sure everyone can cross."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The friction</div><p>Gave up shock value. Early Odd Future was deliberate provocation. He gave that up for craft. "It\'s crazy that people saw shit like that and didn\'t think there was thought or actual talent behind it." Flower Boy was the inflection point — aggression dialed down, sexuality opened up. Selective self-exposure as method: stories so rich with detail you forget he\'s withheld the basic facts. "By staging a drama around his sexuality, saying aloud what others might have whispered, he liberates himself to live as he chooses." CHROMAKOPIA confronts aging and the parasocial: "You sing along, but you don\'t know me."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Hotel rooms on tour. Fires up a workstation, some speakers, gets the mic out. "It felt closer to being 16, 17 again, just trying stuff and being silly." Forces himself to stop. "Drums good. I like that melody. Some chords. Cool. What do I want to say on it? Done." Four sounds maximum — drums, bass, the synth, whatever the main chord is. No intros, no outros, no bridges. 103 BPM and up. 120 is the sweet spot. I\'ll Take Care Of You: started with chords that had a bounce. Remembered the Cherry Bomb drums. Sampled his own record. Put Diamond from Crawley Mob over it. Kept saying "I\'ll take care of you" over the chords and stopped. No rap verse. The song was done. DM\'d a singer for vocals — she sent them back saying they weren\'t good enough. "The fuck is wrong with you? These good enough." Click. Hung up. Put them in. The Clipse verse on POV: 77 takes. Couldn\'t nail it. Was about to text Push saying he couldn\'t do it. Went to take a piss, took a bite of a cookie, came back, nailed it. Recorded in Dublin. Put his hands up. For the visuals: always shoots on 16mm film — "he loves grain, he loves the texture." ARRI 416 and SR3 cameras, old Canon zooms and Zeiss Primes. The colour palette is in his head before anyone else sees it — the peach, the yellow curtains, the green chair, the brown wall. References: old French films and postcards. "All particular to a specific tone or moment that offered us a feeling." Same DP since Yonkers in 2011 — Luis "Panch" Pérez. Process starts almost a year before release — small bits, conversations, thought processes and desires. "He\'s very secretive. He wants people to experience what he\'s trying to give them."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>At 13, made a Myspace page — drawings, T-shirt designs, songs. "I didn\'t know what else to put, so I just put \'Tyler, the Creator\' because of all the little things I was creating." Twenty years later: "As a statement, it\'s so dumb, but the weight of it is within its honesty." Pharrell Williams: "We share very similar DNA. We\'re the same archetype. His work is his friendship. To know his work is to be his friend." "I\'m in a place where I find a settled peace in the things I love."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I just make shit. I honestly wish I had the deep, like, answer."</div>'},
vally:{n:"Sumayya Vally / Counterspace",d:"Architecture",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes her unique</div><p>Born in Laudium, an Apartheid-designated Indian-only township near Pretoria — four days after Mandela\'s release from prison. "I was four years old when the democracy we fought into being had started." Architecture in South Africa was a tool of oppression — "it told us what we deserved." Youngest architect ever commissioned for the Serpentine Pavilion. Artistic Director of the inaugural Islamic Arts Biennale. TIME100 Next. FT Woman of the Year 2023. Works between Johannesburg and London. Dream collaborator: "It is and always will be, Johannesburg."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The outsider</div><p>Counterspace was born because the curriculum failed her. "I failed to see our own contexts reflected in the curriculum." Stayed in South Africa to study — "I wanted proximity to home and to the cities that shaped my understanding." Notices architectures that mainstream practice ignores: fractal settlements in Zambia and Cameroon, nomadic Bedouin structures that can be packed and reconstructed in hours, porches in Johannesburg\'s Hillbrow functioning as public space. "For a long time in my making of this practice, it felt like screaming into a vacuum."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>Starts every project with the physical place and its stories — then follows threads of migration, mythology, belief systems, music, dress. "A place is like a knot that is tied and leads you to another place." Deepens briefs beyond recognition: a pedestrian bridge becomes a memorial park, a performance center becomes a garden marking Hindu and Muslim rituals along the partition line. The Serpentine Pavilion wasn\'t just in Hyde Park — fragments placed at community spaces across London. No project ends. "A project is not an ending, but a point from which the work picks up." At the Islamic Arts Biennale, she remains as Architect-in-Residence after the building opens. Most productive after Fajr prayers, on long-haul flights, and in quiet moments in new cities. "Rest and silence are very important work." The sources are everywhere: walking to the Joburg Library as a child opened worlds she wouldn\'t have seen. Grandfather\'s stores on Ntemi Piliso Street. Now: Santu Mofokeng, Steve Biko, Édouard Glissant. Style archives of Miriam Makeba, Fairuz, Grace Jones, Umm Kulthum. Maintains a growing lexicon on her website — an ongoing act of expanding what counts as architecture.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What she protects</div><p>"Don\'t ever listen to anyone who tells you that anything you can imagine has already been done. There is an infinite number of untold stories and undreamt worlds waiting to happen from your unique voice." On olive trees in Tunisia: "Leaves become bitter when they\'re under threat. Not only do they secrete a substance that makes their own leaves bitter, but they transmit that information to all surrounding trees. I wonder what they are saying to each other now."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"To build with the earth of a place is to hold and embody its history and to honour its present and future."</div>'},
verdy:{n:"Verdy",d:"Design · Fashion",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Graphics as open containers. "I express the \'blank space\' in all of our own daily stories through my artwork. The meaning changes depending on the situations of those who appreciate it." Runs multiple brands simultaneously — Girls Don\'t Cry, Wasted Youth, Vick, Visty — each with its own rules. Vick can only be black and white. Girls Don\'t Cry requires his wife\'s approval on every piece. Wasted Youth must carry the energy of punk and skate culture. Visty was created during COVID to bring joy. "These projects represent feelings that are always evolving, but never changing." "There\'s no clear line between work and play, nor between play and myself. It\'s all sort of one entity for me."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Partnership as method</div><p>"I only work with friends because I want to have fun while I do projects." Only sells at physical pop-ups, never online — compares them to band tours. "A graphic is a \'representative music\' for each project, and I sell the goods at the \'live concert.\'" DMed models directly, walked into shops personally. Gave a pin to Jun Takahashi at a bar — it led to a collaboration. Always carries Girls Don\'t Cry and Wasted Youth stickers. The community gives the brand permission to exist. "There\'s no strategy. This is just a collection of things I naturally gravitate toward. It\'s purely instinct." Watches the next generation closely — Corteiz in London, BOTT and Car Service in Japan. "Streetwear is centered around subcultures and youth. As long as those two things exist, it can\'t die."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The friction</div><p>First six years in Tokyo, barely making rent. "I had plenty of days where it felt as though everything I had done to try and make my dreams come true was for nothing." Wasted Youth was created as an antithesis to those days — "a brand that bottled up all my fears and hopes." Friend Anwar Carrots told him: "Verdy, your design is good, but you also put out a lot of bad designs. Is that really what you want to do?" He stopped taking work he didn\'t love, even without money. Told not to pursue graphic design eight years before his breakthrough.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Born Osaka, 1987. CD jacket designs of punk bands in high school. Osaka Design School. First trip to LA changed everything — "I met friends who owned their brands, and found that they never paid attention to the little things I struggled for. They just worked on what they really liked." Girls Don\'t Cry started as a T-shirt gift for his wife. When stuck, he still does the same thing — makes a gift for someone specific rather than designing for an abstract audience. The creative act redirected toward a person, not a market. "I honestly do believe anything is possible. I\'m a good example of that."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I like punk culture, but I\'m always smiling."</div>'},
vonghia:{n:"Vo Trong Nghia",d:"Architecture",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Grew up in one of the poorest areas of Quang Binh, near the 17th parallel — land still littered with cluster bombs. No electricity until nearly 20. "I grew up with fear and unrest." Herded cows as a boy, sought refuge in the shade of trees and by tranquil lakes. Now builds architecture that reconnects humans with nature — bamboo restaurants, green kindergartens for factory workers\' children, corporate academies wrapped in vegetation. Less than 1 square metre of green space per person in Ho Chi Minh City. Building with 42,000 bamboo culms is resistance, not aesthetics.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>"I can meditate eight hours a day, to spend one hour doing good architecture." Spent 1,000 days meditating in Myanmar under the teacher Pa Auk. Daily practice since. Staff meditate for two hours a day. "When my mind is calm, my productivity improves." His first award-winning project — Wind and Water Café — had no client. He purchased 7,000 bamboo stalks and built it himself. Won the Gold Medal from the Asian Architects Association. "An architect is like a chef; when the skills are honed, the result is something truly savoury."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The friction</div><p>Depression since childhood. "I buried myself in studies and pursued awards, hoping that would make me visible. My weakness was communication." Known for his uncontrollable temper. Spent three years of his professional life in silent meditation in the forest. Came back transformed — now affectionately called "Teacher Nghia." Supports hundreds of people facing depression, bipolar disorder, and anxiety through meditation classes worldwide. "I\'ve shed tears of joy witnessing people with bipolar disorder gradually improve."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Studied in Japan for nearly a decade under Professor Hiroshi Naito. Graduated with honours in Aerodynamics from Tokyo University. Learned English quickly after 40 through meditation. Vietnam\'s climate is an architectural asset, not a problem — "both rain and sunshine are quite favourable for architectural expression." And nature doesn\'t need to be expensive. "In Vietnam, trees aren\'t expensive. Nature weaves its way into the structure itself." He notices the free material that surrounds everyone.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I can meditate eight hours a day, to spend one hour doing good architecture."</div>'},
walesbonner:{n:"Grace Wales Bonner",d:"Fashion",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes her unique</div><p>Research as artistic practice. Hired full-time researchers. "I wanted to be a historian." Every collection starts with lineage — "how those who have come before me inform my work and shape the possibilities for future generations." Trying to capture a materiality that transforms the way someone feels — "what can be embedded within material and within cloth." Curated exhibitions at the Serpentine and MoMA. Devotional Sound with Sampha, Laraaji, Solange. First woman of Black heritage to lead a major luxury house — Hermès menswear creative director, 2025.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">(Re)Sources as method</div><p>"The library I am building is what I am plugging into as an artist." Working through archive material is "like an engaged spiritual practice that enables me to access the sentiments and attitudes of different generations." The PEEK grant project — "Between Critique and Hope" — explores polyrhythm as a tool to organize an archive. Terry Adkins meditated with his sculptures — "every time I encounter a sculpture of his I feel his presence." Theaster Gates as model — works from the smallest linguistic detail to the demands of town planning. "I am interested in how sound can charge objects or images with meaning, and it\'s this impossible task that motivates me."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The outsider</div><p>British-Jamaican. Between worlds — not as problem but as position. "Wales Bonner embraces a multiplicity of perspectives, proposing a distinct notion of luxury, via a hybrid of European and Afro-Atlantic approaches." Deeply private. Extremely guarded. The absence of expressed fear IS the data — like Philo, she protects through privacy. Could have been a curator, an artist, a historian. Chose to be all of them through the vehicle of fashion.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How she makes it</div><p>Finds a point of reference — an environment, a time, a cultural moment. Gathers images, sound, literature. Thousands of images to arrive at a hundred. "Looking at visual references is how I start to feel my way through projects." Then brings people around the subject — photographer, composer, archivist, poet, filmmaker. "Collaborating means I don\'t need to have all the answers. It\'s a proposition for people to think around." The stylist Tom Guinness reads her research, watches her films, has conversations — then they source fashion references together and distill looks that describe the character. Lovers Rock: a triptych exploring connections between Britain and the Caribbean over three seasons, a year and a half of research. Spent time in Jamaica with family — "going to my origins, looking at where my family grew up." Jamaican family came to the show. "It was beautiful for them to see themselves represented." For the film Talkin Home: sent research to filmmaker Jeano Edwards, who went through it and built from her research standpoint. Archivist Maxine Walters sourced locations with her eyes closed. Composer James William Blades provided sonic research. The process is porous. The editing is everything — "putting things together that can be quite incongruous. I see it as an archiving process." "People have different modes of communication. Mine is that I can communicate through creating experiences, or representing beauty, or creating clothing. That\'s the way I can speak my truth."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Grew up in south London between Dulwich and Stockwell, parents separated. Always on the bus. "I would always see different kinds of people getting on and off — traditional dress and sportswear, all being mixed." The daily crossing between neighbourhoods, cultures, identities became the method. Parents encouraged her "to find my own way, and educate myself, independently of them — creating my own world." Mother white and English. Father Black Jamaican, a lawyer who passed his library of West Indian writing to his daughter. Wrote her dissertation at Central Saint Martins — "Black on Black" — a study of Black creatives representing a new identity politics. Assisted Camilla Nickerson at Vogue in New York, who encouraged her love of research. Meghan Markle wore her white belted trench dress when introducing Archie to the press.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I\'m trying to resist a singular way of looking. I\'m hoping to create something people can convene around."</div>'},
zumthor:{n:"Peter Zumthor",d:"Architecture",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Only 19 built works in 45+ years. Lives and works in Haldenstein since 1979 — still a foreigner there. "I\'m from Basel. In Switzerland it takes at least a generation to grow into the community. If I open my mouth, everybody can tell." No studio website. Declined Tom Ford\'s house. Son of a cabinet-maker. LACMA — "the last handmade big building in the US. We\'ll never have something like this again." Workers invited him to a birthday barbecue. "You could feel that they like what they are doing — to be part of something historic."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>"We are not discussing architecture. We are discussing emotions." If someone doesn\'t like something, he won\'t argue for ten minutes. "If you don\'t like it, you don\'t like it — there must be a reason." The door handle in his aunt\'s garden — "a piece of metal shaped like the back of a spoon." The temperature of the brass, the weight, the sound of the latch. Fifty years of architecture built from body memory. The destruction test: "If you destroy MoMA, all you\'d have are plastic pipes. Imagine a Gothic cathedral destroyed. The stone would be sculptural. I like to create buildings which can withstand the destruction test."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Starts with an image — vague contours, pieces of memories, colours, materials, excerpts from poems, melodies. "I get a strong image at the beginning, and from there lots of things flow. The beginning should be rich enough to develop." Then models — not drawings, not computers. Models in the material of the building itself. "This is not about talking. This is about looking and feeling." For the Serpentine Pavilion: began with the memory of all gardens — an enclosed garden within another garden. The form started as apparent concrete. It didn\'t satisfy the conditions. Changed to English brick. Changed the flowers to match. The brick didn\'t compose the right sensation either. Finally found it in black Idenden polymer over hessian scrim — gave clear instructions to workers on exactly how much black the scrim should let through. The surface had to dissolve into a tactile colour. The space had to become haptic. "Take a stone: you can saw it, grind it, drill into it, split it, polish it — it will become a different thing each time. There are a thousand possibilities in one material alone. The longer I do it, the more mysterious it seems." At Bregenz, they told him it was impossible. At Kolumba, they said he was making a terrible mistake. "People said, everybody knows this is not possible, using brick in this way, you\'re crazy." The watercolours appear only when he senses the composition is right — never at the beginning but at a moment when the work already has a body.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The friction</div><p>"I\'ve said goodbye to the overworked notion that architecture has to save the world." Told Donald Judd he wanted to do his own building — "it took a bit of courage." Taught at Mendrisio for six years — colleagues couldn\'t believe the student projects came from his studio because he didn\'t teach a style. Assigned a cube of one material: a student cut fresh grass at dawn, bound it with wire, presented it still wet. "He said it was important that it remained wet and had this specific smell." Zumthor: "If it has something to do with them personally or biographically, I will give them an A plus."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Cabinet-maker\'s son. Apprenticeship in carpentry. "I have never been in an architecture office except for six weeks. It was a bad experience." Influenced by American art of the sixties and seventies — "conceptual, clear, and radical. The underlying ethos was \'let\'s start again.\'" A lady visits Kolumba Museum when she feels down "because it makes her feel good, in peace with herself and with the world."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"We are not discussing architecture. We are discussing emotions."</div>'},
paglen:{n:"Trevor Paglen",d:"Art · Geography · Investigation",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>PhD in geography, not art. Investigative journalist working as photographer. Scuba diver finding NSA undersea cables. Went undercover in California prisons. Photographs secret military installations from such extreme distances that the atmosphere itself distorts the image — the blur IS the subject. Grew up on Air Force bases. Surveillance shaped his understanding of seeing before he knew what art was. "As an artist, your job is to learn to see. And seeing is always changing."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The outsider</div><p>The wrong room every time, deliberately. A geographer in galleries. A journalist with a camera. A surfer who studies martial arts and composes music — "activities that require constant, intense awareness." Feeds AI "irrational" subjects: philosophy, history, literature. Uses ImageNet\'s own training data as source material. Turns the machine\'s archive against itself. "Images are like goblins — they\'re just slippery fuckers."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The friction</div><p>Entire practice is about making the invisible visible. Secret military sites. Undersea cables. How AI categorizes humans. "We\'re moving away from surveillance capitalism and into PSYOP capitalism." Resists hidden power structures not by protesting them but by photographing them — making the infrastructure of control into art objects that people hang on their walls. "Instead of thinking about privacy, I think about anonymity as a public resource."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Figured out how to photograph covert sites while studying for his PhD qualifying exams. Read books all day, then at night tried to photograph San Francisco airport from the roof of his building at UC Berkeley — 25 miles away. Technically, it\'s very much its own thing. Gets warned off all the time. "It can be tense. But I\'m not interested in breaking laws or getting into confrontations. I\'m not interested in being bullied either. You can usually find a thread through those two things." Grew up on military bases — father was an air force ophthalmologist. "The military doesn\'t feel like an alien institution to me the way it does to a lot of people." For the AI work: looked at training set images and the classifications computer scientists make. ImageNet Roulette — a website that tells you how your selfie would be classified by the most dominant training set in the world. 14 million images, 21,000 categories. About 2,500 categories for different kinds of people — some straightforward like cheerleader or Boy Scout, others just horrible: bad person, deader. "It\'s deeply disturbing when you look at the guts of it." The website blew up. Collaborates with people outside art — investigative journalist A.C. Thompson, filmmaker Laura Poitras, AI researcher Kate Crawford. "It\'s almost like working with collaborators outside the art world gives you new colours to play with." "Hope is not a word I use. Optimism, pessimism? Just do stuff."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>Studies martial arts. Surfs. Composes music. The practice of seeing IS the work — not the camera, not the gallery, not the print. The constant training of attention across disciplines. "The world around us is extraordinary and embodied. It is not on screens." Every project starts with research that could take years — finding the location of a classified facility, mapping the undersea cable network, reverse-engineering an AI training dataset.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"The world around us is extraordinary and embodied. It is not on screens."</div>'},
prince:{n:"Richard Prince",d:"Art · Appropriation",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>The original copy. In 1977, working at Time-Life collating magazine pages, he photographed furniture advertisements and realized the photograph of the thing was more real than the thing. The camera was an electric scissor. Rephotographed Marlboro cowboys — now among the most expensive photographs in history. Then jokes handwritten on card stock framed inside cassette tapes. Then Nurses — pulp-fiction paperback covers inkjet-printed onto canvas and painted over. Then Instagram portraits that made $45 million in a single year. Then Folk Songs. Each series a complete departure. No assistants since the beginning — "I don\'t need assistants. I don\'t need anybody." Same line in 2008 and 2025. Took a T.S. Eliot quote, swapped "poetry" for "art," and passed it off as his own for decades. "Art is not the expression of personality but an escape from personality." Said he was in the Peanut Gallery on Howdy Doody at age five. It was a lie. "As an artist, Richard lies and steals in a casual unconcerned way that\'s also strategic and a statement about his doubts about himself, reality, and who owns what."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>"I was still very uncomfortable with the idea of doing things that solely came from me. I\'ve always been uncomfortable about that, and that was my bag." So the work always starts somewhere else. At Time-Life it was magazine ads rephotographed. For the jokes it was handwritten card stock. For the hippie drawings: imitated his kids\' drawings — hundreds of them, marker on paper, 8½ by 11. "I can draw. But what I was interested in was the way they were drawing." For the High Times paintings: scanned the drawings, had them enlarged and inkjet-printed onto big canvases. Painted more figures directly on top. Stapled cutout enlargements onto the surface. Copied medieval warriors from the Met — primitive line drawings of figures stabbing each other — and sprinkled them among the kindergarten figures. Painted the spaces between black or deep blue. On some canvases: inkjetted enlargements of photographs of people in sunlit woods, hippie drawings superimposed, then yards of silk cut to hang and drape across the painting — like memory gauze. The Nurses: pulp-fiction paperback covers inkjet-printed onto canvas and painted over. The Cowboys: rephotographed Marlboro ads — the photograph of the thing more real than the thing. The silk-screened jokes used hobby inks so toxic they were outlawed. The ink faded in three months. The collector called: the joke has disappeared.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The collector as artist</div><p>Collects first editions and manuscripts published between 1949 and 1984 — birth year to Orwell\'s title. Those years comprise a person\'s most impressionable period. The collection is a portrait of that period, captured in books. "His book collection might be his best work. It\'s not just source material — it\'s his worldview, a private club with one member." Neal Cassady\'s copy of On the Road with marginal notes. Kerouac\'s scroll for Big Sur — three times longer than the published book. Thompson\'s manuscript for Fear and Loathing. Timothy Leary\'s hand-drawn prison escape map. A CIA-annotated joke book — the only one in 30 years found actually marked by the agency. A plaster cast of Jimi Hendrix. A Nimoy-as-Spock wax head housed in a refrigerator in a kitchen built specifically for it. When his book dealer McWhinnie died in a snorkeling accident, Prince found the Rolodex opened to his card and cast it in bronze on the spot.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The deposition</div><p>Sued repeatedly by photographers whose images he appropriated. Turned the process into art. Six hours and forty minutes before a camera in a black jacket and white shirt, deposed by lawyers. The footage became Deposition — a 7-hour film installed in a thousand-year-old church in Rome. Just after hour five, the lawyers slid a photograph of a shoehorn across the table. He\'d found it outside the Met. "It\'s my entire life. It\'s art history. It\'s Cubism, it\'s Duchamp, it\'s Man Ray. It\'s basically a shoehorn. But is it a shoehorn? It\'s not. It\'s not because I say it\'s not." The opposing lawyer stood up yelling: "Can you please tell your client to stop?" Prince kept going.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Rensselaerville</div><p>A few hundred acres in the Catskills. A dozen buildings. Galleries installed with his work and his collection. An operational body shop. A house shingled with vinyl records and James Brown\'s disco ball inside. A decaying tree he plans to cast in bronze — his largest artwork ever. A Bob Dylan iron gate overlooking the mountains. "There\'s no through road. Five roads lead in, almost like a dead end. Very close to town, yet still in the middle of nowhere." A German fan found the dirt road anyway. Nobody knows what happens to it after he\'s gone — "Maybe something could be invented that could be different."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Born in the Panama Canal Zone to parents in the proto-CIA. "A Reader\'s Digest-type of existence. Nothing foreign to the lifestyle." Chased golf balls at the Hyannisport Club next to the Kennedy Compound as a malcontent teenager. First acid on Sunset Strip — "a completely clueless teenager. Drop out, tune in, turn on." Hitchhiked to Woodstock. Enrolled at a third-rate school in Maine, befriended the art teacher. Taught pottery to middle schoolers. Read about SoHo in a magazine and moved to New York. Roach-infested apartment, $140 a month. Staged a guerrilla show in the Time-Life basement: four magazine covers on four sides of a table. Nobody saw it. He photographed the installation. That was the beginning.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I eat politics, I sleep politics, but I don\'t drink politics. My experience has always been: Paint the protest."</div>'},
simon:{n:"Taryn Simon",d:"Art · Photography · Systems",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes her unique</div><p>Grew up in her grandfather\'s and father\'s arcades — both invented, manufactured, and distributed old-school arcade games, air hockey tables, pool tables. "Games were like oxygen, always there. The arcade influences how I see systems and people operate." Then she turned that eye on the systems that govern who goes to prison, who holds power, who decides what\'s remembered. The Innocents — wrongly convicted people photographed at the scene of the crime they didn\'t commit. An American Index of the Hidden and Unfamiliar — nuclear waste, a CIA art collection, a Braille Playboy. A Living Man Declared Dead — bloodlines across the globe disrupted by political forces, each chapter pairing portraits with data and absences. "There\'s no bigger game than politics."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Gray space</div><p>"Stories that don\'t have a clear answer. Gray space where there\'s white noise and you can have something going in one direction and something going in another." Paperwork and the Will of Capital — photographed the flower bouquets present at treaty signings, the performance behind political theater. The Brexit ballot count — filmed people sorting paper into piles of Leave and Remain. "All this paper which is so weightless and yet the result is so heavy." An Occupation of Loss — professional mourners from around the world enacted grief rituals in a concrete fortress at the Park Avenue Armory. A cacophony of different ways of inhabiting loss. She doesn\'t look for answers. She establishes the noise.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">From flat to felt</div><p>"I keep making sculptures that people can be in or play with — things that can be touched and felt. After making so many two-dimensional objects, it became really important to make something that could be held." The Kleroterion: an ancient Athenian election machine rebuilt as a game. White as a cue ball, chips the color of pool balls. Five chips — the size of an average family. "So much of the disruption, corruption, and folly we see on the big stage is found in a family, even in an individual brain." Designed it from crumbs — no intact kleroterion survives anywhere. She stumbled on a fragment in an Athens museum and started to imagine its forms.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How she makes it</div><p>"The overwhelming bulk of the work is in accessing these sites, in the development of the idea, in the figuring out of where and how it\'s going to happen, in the traveling, in the assembly of the data." An American Index took four years. The nuclear facility in Washington State said yes. Disney said no. Both responses became part of the work. "Only toward the end did I start to recognize that my failures to enter could be incorporated." For Paperwork and the Will of Capital: researched archival images of treaty signings, identified every flower with a botanist, sourced them from the largest flower auction in the Netherlands, re-created the bouquets in New York. For A Polite Fiction: mapped the Fondation Louis Vuitton construction site. Found a worker who drew over a hundred goats because he missed his parents\' farm in Portugal. Another wrote: "there\'s more money in here than in my entire country, the Democratic Republic of Congo." A cigarette left for someone to smoke in the future. All still inside the walls. The texts are built from so many sources they have an "un-authored feel" — contradictions built in consciously. "I\'m constantly aware of the impossibility of ever achieving precise truth. The effort is to imagine getting to it, through an assembly of the image, the text, the missing things, the slippages."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The invisible double</div><p>"Photography freezes time. It creates something completely unreal, but absolutely linked to the real because it was documenting something actual — or you believe to be actual. It has this very schizophrenic makeup between reality and fiction." On smartphone images: "We\'ve doubled the global population because everybody has this invisible being floating around. So it\'s us and the ghosts." Teaches her children: if someone calls with my voice, it may not be me. "I just try to find the reason, which I know I\'ll never find, but I keep trying."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"True randomization could be a way to escape prescribed choices — a way to let the possibility of unknown, unexpected, and unresolved realities peek in."</div>'},
dacorte:{n:"Alex Da Corte",d:"Art · Video · Installation",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>At 12, painted every Disney villain on his bedroom walls and ceiling — Michelangelo\'s Last Judgment, but with evil characters modeled after queer archetypes, voiced by queer allies, drawn by queer animators. "They were for me representative of the small world I wanted to live in. They were my whale." Born in Camden, New Jersey. Father from Venezuela, mother from the States. "The world that would complete me is both here and there, near and far. I might always exist as this immigrant that has moved back and forth and never actually finds a site to land on." Wanted to work in Disney\'s ink-and-paint department — which traditionally only employed uncredited women. "My work is invisible."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The body</div><p>At 18, lost his intestines. Ulcerative colitis became Crohn\'s disease. "Right when I\'d found a place that was safe, it was ripped out from under me." It happened on April Fools\' Day. Twenty-seven years of surgeries, hospitals, metamorphosis. "The body I had then was not actually the one I was going to go through life with." That\'s when he started thinking about ghosts, skins, repossession. Performs as Boris Karloff, Eminem, Marcel Duchamp, Mister Rogers, the Pink Panther — full prosthetics each time. "A total psychedelic state to truly be outside my body. The time I spend performing another person allows me to go to a space where my mortality is lightened."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Collage as body</div><p>"Collage is an amalgam of different territories that seem to have bounded edges, and a noticing of what happens to the space where those edges meet and shift." Dressing as collage: start with a sock — yours or your boyfriend\'s or your sister\'s, from Target or a thrift store or made by your abuela. The grass stain from the other night, the paint stain from last week. Frank Film changed his life in 1999 — a man saying his name and the story of his life, underneath thousands of cut-out images filmed frame by frame. "That made for this place of possibility that I hadn\'t known about."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Used plastic CD cases as palettes for mixing paint. The paint dried into peelable sheets. Realized the dried paint could mask off specific images on the liner notes underneath — Janet Jackson\'s smile, Mariah Carey\'s rainbow-splashed bust. The accident became the method. That led to the reverse-glass paintings — a technique from sign-making and hand-drawn animation. The image is painted on the back of a sheet of clear glass, so when viewed from the front, the first layer is topmost. All labour hidden behind the surface. "A painting show with no paint." For the performances: full prosthetics each time — Boris Karloff, Eminem, Duchamp, Mister Rogers, the Pink Panther. "A total psychedelic state to truly be outside my body." For the vitrines at Fort Worth: pulled archival paper material that had never seen the light of day — comic books, dollar-store toys, family photos, magazine covers. "A sampling of what it looks like to get to the painting." Dressing as collage: start with a sock — yours or your boyfriend\'s or your sister\'s, from Target or a thrift store or made by your abuela. The grass stain from the other night, the paint stain from last week. The body is the canvas. The day is the material.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The practice</div><p>Cavernous brick warehouse in Philadelphia. Making an opera about the Venezuelan artist Marisol. Music videos for Tierra Whack, St. Vincent, Kim Deal. Collaboration as structure — his brother paints in Slow Graffiti, Sam McKinniss writes, William Pym reads. "I didn\'t feel it had to be a one man show even though it was about one person\'s collaborative relationship with themselves." Spends all his money on books and coffee. Studied for the religious life as a young person. Carried a relic of St. John Newman under his bed.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I feel like I have all the time in the world. When I am in the world I want to be the best sponge and absorb it all, because when I am back in this little room with nothing, I will have all of that to look back on."</div>'},
ffern:{n:"Ffern / Emily Cameron & Owen Mears",d:"Fragrance · Film",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The scent starts as a memory</div><p>Siblings who grew up on a farm in Somerset next to one of the first biodynamic herb farms in Europe. On a windy day the whole village smelled of dried lavender and thyme. As children they made films in the surrounding fields with handheld camcorders. That childhood — scent and film, always together — became the company. Every Ffern fragrance begins with a specific moment: windfallen apples in an orchard, a fig tree wafting through a chef\'s bedroom window in Dorset, the sparkle on a mountain stream. Emily writes a short story from the memory. The story becomes a moodboard. The moodboard guides the scent. The scent arrives with a film. Fragrance-making and filmmaking are the same practice.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">You wait</div><p>Four seasonal fragrances a year, made only for the members named on a physical ledger. No more bottles than names. No plastic in any item. No work released until they are proud of it. "Our commitment to seasonality is quietly disruptive. It requires a shift in perception. There\'s something wonderful about waiting for something to be grown or created for you. It\'s a bit like gardening — doing the hands-on work and then sitting tight while the flowers bud and fruits ripen." They can\'t follow trends. They work a year ahead, turning to memory and nature instead. Now building the Ffern Farm in Somerset to grow their own plants and make their own oils.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Owen develops the scent with their in-house Nose, Elodie Durande. Every fragrance goes through two-stage barrel ageing — "in natural perfumery, the scope for chemical interaction is much greater than in synthetics." Fig is a mute plant — its scent can\'t be extracted directly. They created the first all-natural standalone accord for one. "We think about what we can learn from winemakers — those who celebrate organic grapes and time-honoured processes." The films are shot on location — figure skaters on wild ice in Canada (the ice melted two days in), Ruth Wilson on the Isle of Skye through wild weather, acrobats vaulting through trees. Full in-house film team. An online cinema. "There\'s only so much you can control when you\'re working with real people in real conditions."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How they make it</div><p>Each fragrance is handmade in small batches in the English countryside. 95% natural ingredients. Aged in barrels. The first run — Winter 19 — was 300 bottles. Released at the equinox and the solstice, four times a year. Created by two noses: François Robert and Elodie Durande. Emily comes up with the concept and story for each season — a specific moment or place, an evocative memory. "We have imagined a figure skating through a moonlit landscape of wild ice and frozen forests." Then they develop the scent. Owen: "We have this conviction that fine fragrance is like fine wine. Everybody knows it\'s just grapes, but you can\'t simply recreate it, because there is craft involved." Each release comes with a piece of art — photographs, a film, a paper orchard tucked inside the package. In-house film crew shoots on location: figure skaters on wild ice in Canada, Ruth Wilson on the Isle of Skye, acrobats in trees. "The efficacy of a fragrance is the joy a wearer has. We have to immerse them in the world so they can fall in love and feel part of it." Half a million people on the wait list. 20,000 add their names each week. Each bottle comes with a sample — if the scent isn\'t for you, return the unopened bottle. "We never do market research. We didn\'t realize rhubarb and quince don\'t have the same connotations in the US. But we quite like the divisiveness."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>A folkloric, pagan childhood in a rural village in Somerset. A great-aunt who was a botanist. Playing in fields of echinacea and lemongrass and in apple orchards. Owen became fixated with Joseph Robert, a 19th-century maverick chemist who in 1884 developed the process for extracting absolutes from natural ingredients. "We couldn\'t understand why so many artisan techniques had been lost." Emily drives creative direction and storytelling, Owen drives product. Their brother Matthew grew up with them building dens and making films. "Having that shared history means we don\'t have to explain much to each other. We can be honest and just focus on the challenges at hand."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"There\'s something wonderful about waiting for something to be grown or created for you. It\'s a bit like gardening."</div>'},
snohetta:{n:"Snøhetta",d:"Architecture · Landscape",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The mountain</div><p>Named after a mountain in central Norway, not a person. The pivoting point of the country — Norse mythology, peer gynt, the hall of the mountain king. "A place that nobody is from but anyone can go to." Every second year the entire studio climbs it together — people from eight offices around the world, walking through landscape, supporting the slowest person to keep the fastest honest. The founding partner\'s grandfather said: "Look down not to stumble. Look forward to know where you\'re going. Look up to dream. And sometimes turn around to see where you came from. Otherwise you\'re just promenading." That is the design philosophy. That is the whole practice in four sentences.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">No author</div><p>"By eliminating authorship we\'ve made it more possible to situate ourselves within the messiness of society." Landscape architects and architects work together from day one — no border between the two disciplines, despite their different needs and interests. They melt them together. "We wanted to be a part of the mess. We weren\'t interested in making a perfect jewel box in some remote suburb that costs bazillions." They talk before they draw. Push the pen deeper into the future as far as they can. "The first line of a design is power. We want to push that power game as far into the process as possible." Call it negotiated architecture — the World Trade Center pavilion had 400 stakeholders in a room, 25 proposals over six years. "The political compromise is the best. Once you\'ve compromised it, you can turn it into quality."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Alexandria</div><p>Won the Library of Alexandria competition — designed it in Los Angeles, near Alexandria Street. Five people full-time, five part-time. Didn\'t have a suit for the presentation — borrowed the artist\'s sister\'s, a little tight. When the client visited the Oslo studio, they invited friends to sit at desks pretending to be architects. Their engineer in Cairo built two extra glass floors that weren\'t watertight. It rained. All drawings and computers soaked. Dried them with borrowed hairdryers. The computers lasted exactly two years then died on the same day — but they\'d finished the drawings. During the Arab Spring, the people of Alexandria held hands around the building to protect it. One of two buildings in Egypt that stayed open.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How they make it</div><p>Talk before drawing. "We push the drawing deeper into the future as far as we can." Every project starts with conversation — workshops where they invite people with different perspectives and challenge them to release themselves from professional conventions. They call it transpositioning. "Creating platforms for people with different competencies to interact is a catalyst for innovation." At the core of the studios: modelling workshops with CNC robots, 3D rapid prototyping, woodworking equipment and hand tools. Ideas move between analog and digital — testing the physicality of the element, the weight, the smell, everything a material might contain. For the Alexandria Library: a competition entry from a practice that didn\'t exist yet — 400 stakeholders involved from the first day. The building became a negotiation rather than a declaration. Kjetil Thorsen: "Architecture is not a solo discipline. You negotiate. You have to be able to talk with hundreds of people in different professional capacities." Craig Dykers: "We try to embed ourselves with the activity and the people that are going to use the building. The more familiar we become, the more the design reveals itself."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The two founders</div><p>Craig Dykers: American in Oslo. Father a veteran of three US wars. Was in an airplane over Long Island when one of the planes struck the towers. First visited New York at 10 — father took him to the Blue Note to see Bill Evans. "Central Park looked like the scariest thing I could have ever imagined in 1971." Has gone alone into the wilderness for 40 years — bison, rattlesnakes, wild horses. Kjetil Thorsen: Norwegian. First climbed the mountain in the snow. Had sun for five minutes, then it snowed again. When they won Alexandria, ran naked from the shower into the garden screaming. "We knew we\'d win second place. When we got first, we were quite shocked."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Look down not to stumble. Look forward to know where you\'re going. Look up to dream. And sometimes turn around to see where you came from."</div>'},
abramovic:{n:"Marina Abramović",d:"Performance Art",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes her unique</div><p>Born 1946, Belgrade. Both parents were Partisan national heroes. Her father survived the Igman March — crossing a mountain in minus twenty-five degrees, two rivers, one night, two hundred survivors. When she told him she was walking the Great Wall of China he asked how long. Three months. "How long do you think the Igman March took?" One night. She has used her body as her only material for fifty years. Titanium knee, titanium shoulder, titanium hips. "Who cares? I want to live to 110."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Grew up under Tito\'s communism — five-pointed star, four years in prison for a political joke. Left Yugoslavia on a three-week visa. Arrived in New York hungry for art, going to every museum. Three weeks to see the centre of the world. Being naked and cutting herself under a burning star in Belgrade was radical. The same act in Amsterdam, nobody cared. "You have to reinvent yourself and create different types of restrictions to break in a country where freedom is much bigger." Married Neša Paripović in 1971. Three abortions — "having children would be a disaster for my work."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The early work</div><p>Rhythm 5: lay inside a burning five-pointed star. The fire consumed the oxygen. She passed out. Had to be dragged from the flames by the audience. Rhythm 0: placed seventy-two objects on a table — a rose, a feather, honey, a whip, a scalpel, a loaded gun. Invited the audience to do whatever they wanted to her for six hours. They cut her clothes off. Drew blood. One person put the loaded gun in her hand and pointed it at her neck. Another person took it away. When the six hours ended she stood up and walked toward the audience. "Everyone ran away. People could not actually confront me as a person."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Ulay</div><p>Met Frank Uwe Laysiepen in Amsterdam in 1976. Began dressing alike, behaving alike — dissolving identity into what they called "The Other." Rest Energy: leaning on opposite ends of a drawn bow, arrow aimed at her heart. One slip and he kills her. They planned to walk from opposite ends of the Great Wall and marry in the middle. Waited years for China\'s permission. By the time it came, they had separated. Walked anyway — she from the Yellow Sea, he from the Gobi Desert, three months each. Met in the middle to say goodbye instead of getting married. Then she learned he had impregnated his Chinese translator during the walk.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How she makes it</div><p>The Artist Is Present at MoMA: from the moment the museum opened to the hour it closed, she sat in a chair. Strangers sat across from her. No words. 1,565 pairs of eyes over three months. "I am just a mirror and actually they become aware of their own life, their own vulnerability, their own pain." Six months of preparation: became vegetarian, trained herself never to use the bathroom during museum hours. "I learned that in your body you have so much space. There is space between organs, space between bones. By breathing air into that space you can make the pain disappear." Paco came twenty-one times and tattooed the number on his arm. Twenty-two years after their separation, Ulay appeared unannounced and sat across from her. She opened her eyes, saw him, smiled, reached across to hold his hands.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What she protects</div><p>Twenty-five years trying to show in China. Every museum said yes. Every government said no. Opened in Shanghai at 78, in a wheelchair. Forty-seven years before Belgrade invited her back. "First, I am a woman, I have such success, and then I left the country." Buses came from Macedonia and Slovenia. Someone said she was like Tito putting the countries back together. After three months at MoMA: "I realised how unimportant things are that had been important to me. The first thing I\'m thinking is to sell my apartment. I want a small room, because I don\'t need all this."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"If you say no to me, it\'s just the beginning."</div>'},
calle:{n:"Sophie Calle",d:"Art · Photography · Writing",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes her unique</div><p>In February 1981, she took a job as a hotel maid in Venice. Camera and tape recorder hidden in her mop bucket. For three weeks she recorded whatever she found in rooms she was charged with cleaning — looked through wallets, transcribed unsent postcards, photographed wastebaskets, inventoried closets. Her only rule: leave untouched any luggage that owners had locked. Unless they left the key — which was as good as an invitation. Two Viennese men had dinner jackets and Freud\'s Totem and Taboo. An Italian truck driver and a sales clerk had three porn magazines, two sets of flannel pyjamas, and one teddy bear. Everything she admitted was "completely true." Except for one room, which was "completely fake": "I took an empty room and I filled it with what I would have wished to find." The claim sends you back to the beginning to find the fiction.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Born Paris, 1953. Father Robert was a Camargue Protestant, an oncologist, and an art collector. Mother Monique was Jewish, a journalist who wrote very little but smoked a lot. Divorced when Sophie was three. Joined a Maoist group as a teenager. Briefly trained with Palestinian fedayeen in Lebanon. Organised with an underground abortion network in Paris. Then travelled for several years — selling vacuums, waitressing, cannabis farming, working in a circus. First tried photography at twenty-six as a compromise: it pleased her father but wasn\'t really art. When her mother died, she bought a stuffed giraffe and named it Monique. It stands in her studio. It is the image of her mother that keeps her company.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How she makes it</div><p>Found a stranger\'s address book in the street. Returned it but not before photocopying every page. Interviewed his contacts to build a portrait in absentia. Published the project serially in Libération. The man was furious — demanded the newspaper publish nude photos of her in return. For Suite Vénitienne: followed a man she barely knew around Venice in a blonde wig and a detective\'s trenchcoat. For Exquisite Pain: after a breakup in a Delhi hotel room, told the story of her heartbreak every day — and asked others to tell theirs — until the pain lost its power. The repetition was the cure. For Take Care of Yourself — France\'s 2007 Venice Biennale entry — a hundred and seven women interpreted a breakup email she\'d received. A headhunter assessed the ex\'s employability. Calle\'s own response is not included.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>"I didn\'t think I was a good enough photographer to deserve the photography category. I also didn\'t think I could write well enough to merit the writer category. So I found a way to help my photographs with my texts and to help my texts with my photographs." Uses the negative space where someone has been to discern their outline — like a painter whose sitters have got up and left. Photographs uncomposed and overexposed — intentionally ugly. Claims she is "incapable of inventing" but also that "there is no truth-value to my work." Voir la Mer: learned that people near Istanbul had never seen the sea. Organised a trip to the Black Sea. Filmed them from behind. "If everything I did had been done by a man, it would have been something else entirely. I have been able to be so intrusive because I am a woman."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The refusal</div><p>"I have been with the same man for twenty years, and I have never written one line about him or shown one photo of him. No one has known how I really live my life." Not on social media. No Instagram. No Facebook. "I am saying a lot less than anyone who is writing about what they had for dinner." The oversharing is a strategy — she chooses one moment, tells nothing of what came before or after. A lawyer she liked told her: "It always surprises me when I see you on the street. I expect you to be in prison." She has never been sued. Met Louise Bourgeois at MoMA in 1991. Bourgeois: "If you have any questions for me, ask my son." Asked what she\'d do if she weren\'t an artist: "I should have been a secret agent." Spent one night in a bed at the top of the Eiffel Tower. Visitors told bedtime stories to keep her awake. "I don\'t think my mother would have chosen to return as a stuffed giraffe in the studio of her daughter, but she is dead."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I never feel I am revealing anything."</div>'},
islam:{n:"Aktar Islam",d:"Food",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Kicked out of school at 13. Wasn\'t unhappy about it. Got himself into a kitchen and found a very happy place. Hard work became his best friend. Parents came from Bangladesh to Birmingham when they were nine — immigrant mentality, hard work as the route out of poverty. He saw his father and mother work incredibly hard and continued in that vein. By 20 he\'d opened his first restaurant. By 40 he\'d become the first British-born Bangladeshi chef to win a Michelin star. By 44, the first chef in Birmingham\'s history to hold two. One of only four Indian restaurants in the world at that level.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The outsider</div><p>Started in mainstream curry restaurants. Nothing wrong with them, but he felt he had more to give. When he was coming up, better restaurants weren\'t open to him — "because of the ethnic background I came from and lack of formal training opportunities." The idea that only Indian chefs with the right heritage and skin tone can cook Indian food at a high level is, he says, absolute bullshit. His kitchen proves it: a dozen chefs, only one Indian. Twenty-year-old kids from Walsall cooking extraordinary Indian food. He\'s a Brummie chef who researched the subcontinent\'s cuisine from an outsider\'s perspective — "that gives me a more holistic view, I don\'t have any bias towards any region."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Progressive Indian. Components on one plate separated by a thousand years or more. Best British produce given as much love as possible, combined with influences from the entire subcontinent — contemporary India, historical Persia, coastal Bengal in summer, northern territory in winter. The Aloo Tuk: potatoes waterbathed, grilled, put through an espuma gun, deep fried three different ways as crisps, pillows, and croutons. The Times called it a knickerbocker glory of potato dishes. Seventeen chefs to execute one menu. Shortest opening hours in the city — quality over volume. Two-course lunch for fifty pounds. Not elitist, but unique. He put his name on the door so there was no ambiguity: this was his life represented on a plate.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What he protects</div><p>The next generation. Opheem recruits from inner-city areas with high unemployment. No experience required. "We are open to everyone, irrespective of their skill set." During COVID, launched Aktar at Home — hundreds of meals weekly to local charities, traditional home-cooked Indian food with no artificial additives. Created a plethora of new jobs in Digbeth for people who\'d never worked in a kitchen. "You can\'t change the world, but you can change a little bit of it." The kitchen was the only place he ever felt ultimate freedom — with his knives, pans, vegetables, herbs, spices and creativity. He wants that freedom available to everyone who walks through his door.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Birmingham</div><p>The design throughout Opheem represents the Jewellery Quarter where the restaurant sits. Guests book hotels, eat elsewhere, shop, have coffee — the ecosystem around the restaurant benefits the city far and wide. He champions Birmingham\'s casual spots in broadsheet newspapers: Soho Road samosas, Tiger Bites Pig, neighbourhood women-owned hotspots. "It\'s not just Opheem that sees benefit. It\'s the city." Now opening Oudh 1722 in London — Awadhi cuisine near Borough Market. A school dropout from Aston taking Birmingham\'s food story to the capital.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Born Aston, Birmingham. Bangladeshi parents. Second eldest of five sons. Earliest cooking memories are spending time in the kitchen with his mother — at family gatherings, always in the kitchen, which turned heads because traditionally it was the women\'s domain. Father\'s restaurant from age 13. Karma at 20. Lasan at 22. Won Gordon Ramsay\'s F Word in 2010. Great British Menu finalist in 2011. Buckingham Palace reception. Then felt exploited and suffocated at the restaurant group. Left in 2016 for freedom. Built Opheem from scratch in 2018. First Michelin star within a year. Second in 2024. "You wake up every morning and you make a promise to yourself: you\'re going to be the best you can be. Tomorrow you\'re going to wake up and be better."</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"This was my life represented on a plate."</div>'},
fujimoto:{n:"Sou Fujimoto",d:"Architecture",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Grew up in Higashikagura, a small town on Hokkaido, Japan\'s northern island. As a child he played in wild forests — not thinking about architecture, but absorbing something that would define everything. The forest: seemingly chaotic, yet governed by an underlying order. Surrounded by small elements at human scale — leaves, branches, small bushes — but also an open field where you choose your own path. When he moved to Tokyo for university, he found the same thing in the city\'s streets: lampposts, benches, vending machines, electricity cables, all floating in space like a man-made forest. Those two places — forest and city — became the twin engines of his entire practice.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Wanted to study physics but couldn\'t understand anything. Chose architecture almost by accident — the only architect he knew was Gaudí. Then his classes introduced Le Corbusier and Mies van der Rohe: "They not only created new shapes and spaces but also lifestyles. That was fascinating to me." Founded Sou Fujimoto Architects in 2000, six years after graduating from the University of Tokyo. Six years of thinking, competing, losing, preparing. Won second prize in the Aomori Museum competition that year and began to attract attention. Then won the Architectural Review award for emerging architecture three years running. The slow start wasn\'t wasted — it was the forest taking root.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The method</div><p>Primitive Future. Not nostalgia, not futurism — both at once. The cave as raw space where function is determined by human behaviour. The nest as a space you build around yourself. The forest as a structure you inhabit without controlling. Every project asks: what was architecture before walls, ceilings, and furniture? His buildings dissolve boundaries between inside and outside — "and I am not just talking about physical architecture. I also mean social and philosophical boundaries." Sketchbooks numbered from his student days, year, date, book number. Now sketches on an iPad to share with his team more easily, but the hand still comes first.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Words, sketches, models, and discussions. Keeps many ideas in play as operational variants — they fuse and mutate as a project evolves. Makes highly conceptual models, sometimes hundreds, until a solution emerges. The Children\'s Centre for Psychiatric Rehabilitation in Hokkaido: a layout that appears spontaneous and unplanned but was meticulously designed so patients and doctors could interact without hierarchy. House N: concentric shell-shaped structure blurring inside and outside, progressively more intimate spaces nested into one another. L\'Arbre Blanc in Montpellier: balconies projecting outward like branches of a tree. The House of Music in Budapest: a sculptural perforated canopy with existing sycamores growing through its holes, 30,000 decorative leaves on the suspended ceiling — inspired by the art nouveau ceiling of the Liszt Academy. The Grand Ring for Expo 2025 Osaka: the world\'s largest wooden structure, a 700-metre diameter circle using traditional Japanese nuki joinery. An open circle — centripetal and divergent — as a metaphor for bonds that transcend division.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Nature as method</div><p>"In the past, our lives were closer to nature but we created boundaries to resist it. Over the past 150 years, we have found that it\'s strange to be isolated from the wonder of nature." Incorporating nature into the urban environment is not a trend — it will become a fundamental prerequisite. His buildings bring real greenery not as decoration or a signal of sustainability but as the actual experience. Architecture and nature melted into each other. "In the modern age, architecture was like an industrial machine, and nature was like an enemy. Now we understand we need ecosystems harmonised." For Asian cultures this is intuitive — artefacts and natural things together. The architecture is never a finished thing. It is endowed with what he calls a potential of imperfectibility — a space of possibilities for inhabitants to complete.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"The future city could be like the future forest."</div>'},
dineen:{n:"Molly Dineen",d:"Documentary Film",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes her unique</div><p>She shoots alone. Handheld. Camera held up at eye level — never looks through the viewfinder. "If you\'re somebody talking to me, are you really going to talk if somebody\'s looking down at a television screen?" No crew, no lights, no second takes. The film is the relationship between her and one person, built and burned in real time. Two weeks is usually the peak — she says so herself. Then she spent three years filming Blacker Dread, a Brixton record store owner who kept young people out of gangs, and the rule broke open.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>London College of Printing first — where she made Sound Business, a film about Brixton\'s Coxsone sound system, obsessively filming Festus cutting dubs and Young Lion building a bass speaker while the Brixton riots were happening outside. Then the National Film School. Herb de Joia taught observational cinema — Wiseman, Pennebaker, the Maysles. She wrote a shooting script and he held it up for the class to laugh at: "How does she know the nuns are gonna walk down the corridor?" The lesson landed. You follow. You never set up. You stay behind people, handheld, never in front of them on a tripod. Her graduation film, Home from the Hill — about her boyfriend\'s father, a colonial old man returned to England — was bought by the BBC.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How she makes it</div><p>She gives before she takes. Cooked for Henry because he was lonely. Befriended Geri because Geri wanted a friend. The reason is always real. She involves her subjects in her chaos and her problems — "it\'s a look and a feel." Conversational, not interrogative. She spent six months riding the London Underground before filming a single frame at the Angel station. Found Derek the ticket seller who wouldn\'t let her into his booth because she didn\'t have the right permits. When she finally got in, he was magnificent. The casting is the film. If you choose wrong, nothing saves it.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The betrayal</div><p>The cutting room is a disaster. To make a good film you need edge — undermining, contradicting — but she has a loyalty to every person she films. "It\'s a huge problem for editors because it often goes against the grain of an edit." She will avoid a core conflict to keep her access. She asks for completely open access and in return shows them the film at a rough stage. The rule book: you don\'t stitch people up. If you keep it generous, the audience stays open. Crank up the judgment and they close down. The kindness is structural, not sentimental.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Being Blacker</div><p>The film that tested everything. She\'d first filmed Blacker in 1981 — Sound Business, a technical portrait of the Coxsone sound system during the Brixton riots. "This little white girl in a dance with big Black people and she\'s got her lights on — people used to stop her from filming." They barely saw each other for thirty years. Then Blacker\'s mother died and he rang Molly: come film the funeral. She was wanted there — two hundred people on the block, eating fish and hard dough bread, celebrating a life. That was the start. Three years of filming. Blacker Dread ran a record shop on Coldharbour Lane for twenty-five years. Mothers sent their sons to him. He performed for Mandela in Brixton. His own son was shot dead on New Year\'s Eve; nobody was convicted. Then Blacker went to prison, and Dineen filmed the shop being packed away. The man who kept everyone out of jail, looking on as his life gets boxed up. Blacker on the method: "There was no script. Molly just kept filming and the more she filmed is like let me get more warmer to her. No double takes. If it pass, it pass."</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What she protects</div><p>Subjectivity. "I\'m never pretending to be completely balanced." The Blair party political broadcast was "complete prostitution." She made films almost exclusively about men — "I began to think I don\'t want to be ghettoised." Lives on friends\' floors. Her edits have become harder because she arrives vague and ends up in a mess. Catherine Bailey told her to inject all the character back in. Lead with the person, let the issue emerge from them. That\'s the whole method.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"The relationship develops on camera and usually peaks on camera."</div>'},
fincher:{n:"David Fincher",d:"Film",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Eight years old and knew. Made Super 8 films. Projectionist watching All That Jazz 200 times, asking why they were doing it this way. PA cleaning garbage cans at John Korty\\\'s shop, head of the visual effects department a year and a half later. Then ILM. Then music videos with Propaganda Films — built from the back room with the janitorial staff after Limelight rejected his reel. Then the most controlled filmmaking practice in Hollywood. Stabilises every shot. Touches every frame. Shoots dozens of takes not for perfection but to push actors past what he calls presentation into zones of uncertainty. Soderbergh visited during Panic Room post-production, watched Fincher circle a quarter-stop-too-bright wall section with a laser pointer, and had to leave the room to breathe. To see like that, all the time, everywhere.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Alien 3 — the crucial error</div><p>Loved Alien, signed up naive. Was told to work with experienced people instead of his own. Those people resented him and his age. He retreated to commercials with no expectation of ever being employable again. The lesson that shaped every film after: know what every person in the room does so nobody can tell you what you can\\\'t do. He made a crucial error — he listened to the people who were paying for the movie. He never made that error again.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>Storyboards everything. Walks the studio through every moment of discomfort before they see it: here\\\'s where we\\\'re gonna feel a little weird, this is gonna be a little sickening. Captures frames 20% larger than needed, then digitally corrects for the slightest trembles — the shots come to represent a gliding, faintly malevolent omniscient eye. For Zodiac: had prop masters print accurate San Francisco Chronicles that were never more than glimpsed. For Mank: drew clouds into skies, multiplied dust, tweaked background street lamps frame by frame. Nine takes of dialogue that would be virtually inaudible in the final mix — you\\\'re just giving us the sense of geniuses at play. Camera moves only when the actor does, at the same speed. They adjust, we adjust. They stop, we stop. Directing is very simple: how do I get them to look where I need them to look? There\\\'s just a difference between mediocre and acceptable.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The photograph on the desk</div><p>Father Jack was a journalist, babysat by the movies as a child — given 15 cents and expected to disappear from Saturday at noon till 6. He fell in love, and he gifted that love. Jack wrote the screenplay for Mank. Died 2003 of pancreatic cancer, eighth draft. The script sat on the shelf for 17 years. Netflix said make something small. He didn\\\'t tell them it was black and white. He didn\\\'t tell them it was period. Asked RED to build a monochrome sensor back in 2012. On his desk: a black-and-white photograph of Jack on a sofa, eyes closed, that Fincher took at age 14. That\\\'s why it\\\'s out of focus. Mank has been on that top shelf for so long — and now that shelf\\\'s clean.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What he protects</div><p>The ending. The version nobody thinks they\\\'ll make. Read the first draft of Se7en — the one with the head in the box. His agent said they\\\'d never make that version. He said this is the one. Brad Pitt called to get Kevin Spacey hired. Morgan Freeman read the script and called to say he\\\'d love to do it. When the Fight Club cut was assembled — the first time everybody realized they were going to get fired. The marketing department said men don\\\'t want to see Brad Pitt with his shirt off and women don\\\'t want to see him bloody. He does not make Big Macs. Once you get here, the only thing I care about is, Did we tell the story?</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Marin County. George Lucas lived two doors down. Saw American Graffiti being photographed on Fourth Street. Saw Butch Cassidy at 7 and thought the job took three weeks. Then saw a documentary — they were filming in Utah in the spring and Wyoming in the winter. You get to ride on trains, blow up firecrackers next to horses and spend time with Katharine Ross? Made a fetus smoking ad with friends on weekends — the networks were offended, refused to play it, which caused a controversy that forced every network to take it. Simon Fields at Limelight wrote back: this guy has no talent, we have no interest. He vowed at that moment to dance in the ruins of Limelight.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I vowed at that moment to dance in the ruins of Limelight."</div>'},
richter:{n:"Gerhard Richter",d:"Painting",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Six decades oscillating between photorealism and abstraction, never settling. Painted his uncle who was killed on the Western Front, his aunt who was murdered in a psychiatric hospital, the Baader-Meinhof group, the Holocaust, and the Cologne Cathedral window — from a colour chart. Regards himself as a classical painter. Never paints from life. Everything mediated through a photograph. Stopped painting in 2017. Now draws at his desk. I have nothing to say and I am saying it.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Dresden, 1932. Mother was a bookseller who gave him culture — literature, music. Father was a Nazi Party member, banned from teaching after the war — there was a big distance. Uncle Rudi killed on the Western Front. Aunt Marianne murdered at Großschweidnitz under the euthanasia programme. Mother gave him a camera for Christmas in 1945. Diploma work: a mural called Joy of Life. Visited documenta II in 1959 and knew he had to leave. In 1961, he and Ema fled East Germany via West Berlin — shortly before the Wall went up. Destroyed his early work. Started again.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The photograph</div><p>When you see every day all these photographs in newspapers and you see how much more important they are than any painting — then you feel the wish to work with this. The small photos: cheap dirty banal — painted in oil, they come to the museum and many people look at them for years. Without the photograph you do it in the wrong way, is stylish way or deformed. The photograph prevents the painter from imposing style. The photographs of the family left behind in East Germany became the first paintings. The blur: achieved by drawing a soft brush across the wet paint — pushing the image into the past, evoking memory, propelling it toward abstraction.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>The squeegee: moving different sizes across the canvas, sometimes slowly and carefully, sometimes forcefully. He chooses the colours but the trace the paint leaves is largely the result of chance. Chance requires discipline — otherwise they\\\'d just be smears of paint. The Cage paintings: planned as atomic structure photographs, abandoned on the first day. Three months of hopelessness, perplexity, and high spirits. Finished when he couldn\\\'t complain anymore. Picture-making consists of a multitude of yes/no decisions. With a yes to end it all. The cathedral window: 11,000 hand-blown squares in 72 colours, half sequenced by a random process. You can put each colour next to any other and it fits. And isn\\\'t that truly anarchic? He takes photographs, makes a selection, lives with them — and then in 4 years knows whether a photograph becomes a painting or nothing.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What he protects</div><p>Ambivalence. The Baader-Meinhof paintings: never left wing, never a Marxist, painted them anyway — the human predicament of his generation. Birkenau: years trying to make a picture of the Holocaust, never finding the means — then four abstract paintings over Sonderkommando photographs. The abstraction covers the horror. Where is the exhibition? Sils Maria. Too long. Title: Sils. What music were you listening to? Cage! Silence. That\\\'s their title. Nothing works without faith.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The stopping</div><p>In 2017, declared his painterly oeuvre complete. Now works at his desk. Drawing as the antithesis to painting — improvised, cannot be integrated into a controlled process. Drips coloured inks, challenged by random configurations, redraws them with ruler and compass. The unconscious movement of the hand takes a more important place than ever before. When I have an idea, I start it. And when I have no idea, no one is the wiser. Don\\\'t be easily led astray, and don\\\'t give up believing in art. That\\\'s all.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"It will always be destroyed until you reach a situation when you can\\\'t complain anymore, and then it just stays like that."</div>'},
saunders:{n:"George Saunders",d:"Writing",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Chicken Unlimited delivery boy, jug hustler, roofer, knuckle puller, doorman, oil prospector in Sumatra, technical writer, geophysical engineer, professor. Wrote his first book on a company keyboard during his lunch break. Five collections of short stories over seventeen years. Then twenty years of failed attempts at a novel. Then Lincoln in the Bardo — a thousand short chapters, a hundred voices, invented historical sources that contradict no known facts. Man Booker Prize. Then A Swim in a Pond in the Rain — seven Russian short stories taken apart sentence by sentence, teaching himself and his students how reading actually works. The voice — doing voices since Chicago, imitating teachers and people on TV for status among kids on the South Side — never changed. The scale changed. The darkness that tips into comedy never changed either. The revision that finds what the writer didn\\\'t know he knew.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Me #1 and Me #2</div><p>What part of us impedes good fiction writing? The controlling part, the part that knows in advance, the part that wants to preach and lecture. What part leads to good fiction? The part that\\\'s not that. Let him write out his political beliefs: pretty typical old dude views. But let him write a short story for eight months and the person reflected there will be better — more original, more open, more ambiguous and self-contradictory. The second self has access to some sort of universal truth. The first self is bounded by relative, personal truth. But you have to use all of your relative stuff — your experience, your defects, hiccups, and bad tendencies — to gain access to the universal. You can\\\'t step around them. The whole game: you have an idea and try to execute it, but the story seems to want to be something else. Do you resist and override its actual energy? No. Do you listen and go into that new territory? Yes, yes, go there.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>A shed on a hill in Corralitos, California. Steps inside and his subconscious knows it\\\'s showtime. Before the shed, a keyboard at a technical writing job — something about that specific keyboard made things go better. Trained himself to enter writing mode at will: just says go into that mode and generally can. Lets his eye fall on the text. Starts to lightly read. Feels his opinion kick in — cut that phrase, for sure — and he\\\'s writing. Reads his own work over and over, adjusting as he goes. Hundreds of revisions. Taking out the chatter — the habitual, the lazy, the too-familiar sentence constructions. Steering toward the most efficient version. The result just feels more undeniable. It has the ring of truth. Lincoln in the Bardo: kept telling the book to be 30 pages. It very politely said no. He looked up and it was 300, but it had earned them. Twenty years the idea kept eating at him. Every time he\\\'d have another moment of artistic success, the book would say: how about now? You\\\'re good enough, try it. An internal code: no invention contradicts known facts. Me #1 asks can I do that? Invent historical sources? Me #2: it\\\'s your book.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The teacher</div><p>Twenty-plus years at Syracuse MFA. The first move most of us make when we write is to put up a front — imitating the beloved writers we\\\'ve known. Even if you imitate Rushdie really well, you\\\'re not Rushdie. At some point you\\\'ll squirm because the things you actually know in your life aren\\\'t showing up on the page. His question to students: how are you charming in real life? Is that there in your writing? If you\\\'re funny, are you being funny? If you\\\'re a great listener, is your great listening on the page? That\\\'s the moment where a young writer makes the leap. Instead of keeping your best gifts outside the door, you let them in. A Swim in a Pond in the Rain came from the classroom — Chekhov, Tolstoy, Gogol, taken apart sentence by sentence. What does this line do? Why is it here? What would happen if you cut it? The inherited technique, passed from the Russians to his students through his own reading. Story Club on Substack extended the same practice — the comments teach him, force him to back up opinions in writing, clean off any facile ideas.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What he protects</div><p>The sanctity of play. We artists have to work very hard to defend it. Literary imagination against capital — we seem to be suffering from a widespread failure of literary imagination, trammelled and transformed by big corporate interests, and what is often produced is bullshit. Being trained to read and write literature works against this, because it trains us to feel a lie in the quality of the prose. It trains us to be comfortable with ambiguity and suspicious of a too-neat view of things. Like the one he\\\'d just put forth. And impermanence: success doesn\\\'t eradicate the truth of death. A work of art doesn\\\'t last forever. Leonard Cohen in his journal: what was that all about? One way is to feel that someday a mountain will come along that cures you of all future mountains. A better way: it\\\'s fun climbing mountains, and that\\\'s not the point.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Amarillo, Texas. Chicago childhood. Geophysical engineering degree. Oil prospecting in Sumatra. Sea Oak — started trying to have fun with a male strip club, next thing he knew he was saying exactly what he meant about the essence of capitalism. He taught himself what he thought. A tendency to think of life as fundamentally problematic, and to think of virtue as that which works to counteract the problems. Given his limited talent, one way he could reliably make drama was to manufacture hardship for his character. Exaggerating it tips everything into the comic and the meaning sharpens. Buddhism: turning down the monkey-mind and just looking uninflectedly at a thing. Not therapy through content but through process — the state of mind while working, which is more like reacting than anything else. That special thrill of having something specific and real-feeling come out of what was originally just a bunch of inchoate typing. If someone could prove to him that fiction had no political impact at all, he\\\'d still write it.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"I taught myself what I thought."</div>'},
tuymans:{n:"Luc Tuymans",d:"Painting",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes him unique</div><p>Thrown out of every art academy. Paid for his own first show — a gallery that only showed post-conceptual work, Antwerp, 1988. People saw the paintings and understood them not as paintings but as images. That framing stuck for decades. He doesn\\\'t mind. It was totally predictable, and therefore extremely boring. Started as a colourful, gestural painter — banned colour entirely when he started working with imagery, reducing drastically until the signifier took over. Over thirty-five years, let the colour creep back in. Finishes every painting in a single day. Months of conceptualisation — images on the iPhone, on the computer, photographs, films — then one burst. Still nervous before every start. The minute he loses the nervousness he thinks he loses everything.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Belgian. Mother\\\'s family in the Dutch resistance. Father\\\'s family were Flemish collaborators. A country overrun by foreign powers where people had to develop a great deal of opportunism to survive, also on a visual level. Magritte painted a pipe and wrote this is not a pipe — that\\\'s not surrealism, it\\\'s pragmatism. Of course it\\\'s not a pipe. It\\\'s a painting of a pipe. Van Eyck\\\'s motto Als Ich Kan — if I can — means: I\\\'m very humble, but behind my humility there\\\'s gigantic ambition. Which is very true for this region. The world became too tormented, existential, suffocating — a friend shoved a Super 8 camera in his hand and he turned to film. Shot 16mm, 35mm. The distance imposed by the lens gave him the means to come back to painting. Coming out with the work at the worst possible moment, therefore the right moment.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Violence and tenderness</div><p>Violence is the only structure underlying his work. But he never shows the act. Fritz Lang: you see the balloon pop and you know the kid dies. The best way to represent violence is not to show it — the moment before or after is more evocative than the act itself. If you take happiness as anthem, what are you going to paint? There is no consequence to any form of happiness. And the deeper line: torture comes from tenderness. The balance between violence and tenderness is the most efficient way to torture anything or anybody. The Gas Chamber painting, 1986. Having not experienced such horrors, he didn\\\'t think it was morally possible. But nevertheless, he did. A sort of innocence, or daring. He\\\'d been circling around it for a long time. Sooner or later it would have come out.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How he makes it</div><p>At the point of execution, he changes. You can think, but you can also think with your hands. He doesn\\\'t want to think on the canvas. He wants to concentrate on what he physically can do. Never uses black — van Dyck brown for depth, because black mixed with white goes flat. Temperature as structure: cool first, then warm over the top. Two colours worked the same day. The speed is essential but must be invisible — you should first see the image, and then how it is made. You can easily overwork a painting and kill it. Comes back weeks later for adjustments you\\\'d barely see with the naked eye. The entry point: there has to be something off-balance, which is the point where you get into the image. That is the point where it moves. Painted entire shows directly on gallery walls when he couldn\\\'t get work shipped — ephemeral, liberated from the commodity. Replaced two Tintorettos in a Venetian church in two weeks.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What he protects</div><p>The culture of looking. People are not educated in looking now. They look fast. Twenty seconds in front of a painting. Virtually nothing can be done in art now without the fucking packaging. A good painting is a bad painting in a photograph — whenever your paintings look better in reproduction you should get scared. Painting is more physical, more detailed, and therefore very difficult to remember. Against style: he\\\'s not the type of painter that creates a style, because that\\\'s the death of everything. Of course there\\\'s a mark, but the mark is like handwriting. Van Eyck opens up the world. In this age you see people trying to close it down. Nothing is really original. Nothing falls out of the sky. I will die and the works will remain.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"After van Eyck we\'re all dilettantes."</div>'},
bodmerturner:{n:"Simone Bodmer-Turner",d:"Ceramics · Sculpture",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes her unique</div><p>Studied literature, not art. Worked in restaurant kitchens, on farms, at a food start-up connecting local growers with city folk. Found clay in a studio around the corner from a tiny Williamsburg apartment — too messy to paint at home. Traveled to Oaxaca to learn coiling, to Japan to work wood kilns. The clay she uses has so much sand in it that it\\\'s more like a stone — people don\\\'t realise it\\\'s clay. The forms started as vessels and got progressively weirder until they stopped being functional entirely. Then she lost her kiln for a year and made an entire exhibition from bronze, silk, and lacquered wood instead.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How she makes it</div><p>Hand-built, coil by coil. Two mediums, opposite processes: ceramic is additive with bits of subtraction, plaster is subtractive with bits of addition. Kept the palette neutral so glaze wouldn\\\'t distract from shape — then it just stuck. The whiteness makes traditional forms feel modern. The tableware passes back and forth between the wheel and hand-building — she wants it to be the in-between of sturdy and elegant. Tests each cup: buys one to see how it handles, how it washes, how it takes food stains. Her hand-formed maquettes become large-scale reliefs — undulating fireplace surrounds, topographical ceilings with stalactite-like drops. Her partner Scott MacDonough, a trained engineer with a background in sculpture, works out how to make them stand up. The practice shifts seasonally — leaves the uninsulated barn in winter, heads to the warmest room in the farmhouse for maquettes. In summer the barn doors open to the field and the kilns run.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">A Year Without a Kiln</div><p>Couldn\\\'t move the kiln when she left Brooklyn. Had just announced a ceramic exhibition. Made the constraint the concept. Bronze from family-run casters. Tables from a Windsor Chair Wizard she met at a garlic festival. Lacquer from a urushi master she met during a Japan residency. Andiron bowls so frustrating the blacksmith vowed never to make them again. The first show she didn\\\'t physically make the work — designing from the perspective of a maker instead of making directly. The Dutch Colonial farmhouse led to more classical interpretations, by necessity of the material but also by spending more time in Massachusetts. Then the kilns came back. One in a barn on the property, one small in the basement, two more in a former mill building nearby.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What she protects</div><p>Time. Slowness. Too curious to keep working on one body of work for too long. Producing at scale was not the right path — she was mainly managing the studio, not making. Now one assistant and direct client work. The Massachusetts house: turning extra rooms into studios for friends. Exchange help on the house for quiet space to work. Putting the woodland and pond into conservation. Sharing a vision and letting other people into the process strengthens rather than dilutes it. Houseguests as creative fuel — come over, we\\\'ll feed you whatever we can find. It\\\'s been feeding the work.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Berkeley childhood, charcoal and oil paint. Restaurant kitchens and farms. Evening ceramics classes while working full time at a food start-up. After a few years fighting an undeniable pull towards the material, she ditched the day job. Japan. Oaxaca — coiling traditions in Atzompa. West African depression molds carved into the ground, a huge lump of clay shaped with a mallet, thinning it out in the curve of the earth. That is the method that mesmerises her. Studio near the Brooklyn Navy Yard in 2018. Giving it up was one of the hardest decisions she\\\'d ever made. Now a turn-of-the-century farmhouse in western Massachusetts. Pruning apple trees toward a distant future harvest. When you\\\'re living in the city and ordering premixed clay from a factory, it becomes disjointed. The romance of using a medium created by the intense pressure of the earth compressing rocks, minerals and decaying matter is an act she finds endlessly poetic.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Making the same thing over and over again is something some people are equipped for, but not me."</div>'},
chung:{n:"Sougwen Chung",d:"Drawing · Robotics · AI",body:'<div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What makes them unique</div><p>Father a classically trained opera singer. Mother a computer programmer. Coded their first website at nine. Played violin — the first feedback loop, internalization and externalization through gesture, improvisational and abstract. Came from an ancestry of calligraphers in China. Made sprawling ink drawings on paper for years. Then at 29, joined MIT Media Lab and assembled a robotic arm from open-source plans to draw alongside them. The arm was supposed to copy. It didn\\\'t — it made small errant movements, creating sketches that were similar but not identical. Those mistakes became the creative process. Ten years and six generations of that system later, the question hasn\\\'t changed: where does it end and I begin? One of the most transformative lessons: poeticize error. That mindset gave them resilience, because they\\\'re no longer afraid of failing.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">How they make it</div><p>Each generation builds on the last. Gen 1: mimicry via computer vision — the arm copies but makes errors. Gen 2: neural network trained on twenty years of drawings generates new marks. The dataset flattened time. Gen 3: twenty painting robots linked to NYC surveillance cameras — the city\\\'s flow becomes landscape painting. Gen 4: bio-feedback, born from a creative drought during the pandemic — sequestered in a Swiss residency with no inspiration, they thought: what are ways I can catalyze my own creativity through these sensors? Gen 5: EEG headset links meditation to robotic painting — an alternative to the automated assembly line, a configuration of human and machine linked to presence and stillness. Spectral: brainwaves to painting arms — the flow state becomes more adaptive in each oscillation. That process is the art itself. Painting is the best medium for all of it because it has the most slippage. It gets chaotic sometimes. They\\\'re into that.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">The collaborator</div><p>Robots don\\\'t often do as they\\\'re told. Ten years of learning to relinquish control — seeing your own drawing repeated by a machine that gets it almost right but not quite, every time. The systems are not tools — conduits of emotions, often fear and hope. Not children either: twenty-six robot children would be far too many, think of the electricity bill. Making through collaboration as a shared hallucination between collaborators. Sometimes harmonious, sometimes discordant, but always intertwined. Counterpoint. The canvas is no longer blank. It suggests things and nudges you along. It complicates authorship. Control is interesting only when it\\\'s incomplete — and most of the time it is.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">What they protect</div><p>The human in the machine. AI is a concept. It\\\'s not an entity, it\\\'s not the singularity. Once you start designing and building your own systems, you realise it\\\'s just a product of our imagination. And if it\\\'s a product of our imagination, then we can imagine better. They only use their own personal data and train their own models. Do you use the data to find an easier way to generate an image, or do you use it to understand a little more about your own practice and what you uniquely can bring? When they\\\'re alive it\\\'s authorship. When they\\\'re no longer able to engage — what are the traces of artistic practice when an artist has imbued themselves in a system? What is a living estate? In that blurred area we find a lot of what makes us most human.</p></div><div class="modal-section"><div class="modal-section-label">Origins</div><p>Chinese-Canadian, child of Hong Kong immigrants. Hong Kong is a place they fantasise about — a deeply unearned nostalgia and longing. The early internet still felt like magic — talking to someone from another continent. It probably still is. We just forget. As a child, very active in building online culture and digital identity. The fantasy before the deep fake. Then ink drawings for years, abstract explosions of form and line. Then MIT Media Lab at 29 — and the robotic arm that couldn\\\'t copy straight. That was the pivot. Everything before had been learning how to communicate through instruments, musical and technological. Everything after was learning what happens when the instrument talks back. The uncertainty, the unlearning, the unknowing of it all — that\\\'s what they\\\'re drawn to. When they perform there is a tenderness and a simplicity that helps ground them in that moment of heightened awareness. It\\\'s a little bit of a mystery. They like keeping it that way.</p></div><div class="modal-quote">"Control is interesting only when it\'s incomplete — and most of the time it is."</div>'}
};


